ognizes-armenian-genocide |title = Spanish City of Alicante Officially Recognizes Armenian Genocide |publisher = Massispost.com |accessdate = July 29, 2016 }}</ref> [[Torrent, Valencia|Torrent]],<ref>{{cite web |url = http://guanyanttorrent.org/guanyant-torrent-saca-adelante-una-propuesta-a-favor-del-pueblo-armenio/?lang=es |title = Guanyant Torrent saca adelante una propuesta a favor del pueblo Armenio |publisher = Guanyanttorrent.org |accessdate = February 9, 2017 }}</ref> [[Petrer]],<ref>{{cite web |url = http://horizonweekly.ca/en/spanish-city-petrer-recognizes-armenian-genocide |title = Spanish city Petrer recognizes Armenian Genocide |publisher = Horizonweekly.ca |accessdate = April 1, 2017 }}</ref> [[Villena]],<ref>{{cite web |url = https://armenpress.am/eng/news/888719/spainish-city-of-villena-officially-recognizes-and-condemns-armenian-genocide.html|title = Spanish city Villena recognizes Armenian Genocide |publisher = Armenpress |accessdate = April 28, 2017 }}</ref> [[Cullera]],<ref>{{cite web |url = http://www.armradio.am/en/2017/05/03/spanish-city-of-cullera-recognizes-armenian-genocide/|title = Spanish city Cullera recognizes Armenian Genocide |publisher = Public Radio of Armenia |accessdate = May 3, 2017 }}</ref> [[Sueca, Valencia|Sueca]],<ref>{{cite web |url = http://hayernaysor.am/en/archives/249078|title = Spain's Sueca officially recognizes the Armenian Genocide |publisher = Hayernaysor.am |accessdate = June 3, 2017 }}</ref> [[Ontinyent]],<ref>{{cite web |url = https://news.am/eng/news/558387.html |title = Spain's Ontinyent recognizes Armenian Genocide |publisher = News.am |accessdate = February 9, 2020 }}</ref> [[Valencia]].<ref>{{cite web |url = https://news.am/eng/news/394658.html|title = Spain's Valencia recognizes Armenian Genocide |publisher = News.am |accessdate = June 10, 2017 }}</ref>\n[[File:Margadeh.jpg|thumb|Pilgrims commemorating the 94th anniversary of the Genocide in Margadeh, near [[Deir ez-Zor]] in [[Syria]]]]\n;Switzerland \n* {{flag|Geneva}}: Government of Swiss canton of Geneva recognized the Armenian Genocide of 1915<ref>{{cite web |url = http://www.panarmenian.net/eng/world/news/4480 |title = Government of Swiss Canton of Geneva Recognized Fact of 1915 Genocide of Armenians |work = panarmenian.net |accessdate = December 11, 2016 }}</ref>\n* {{flag|Vaud}}: Swiss Canton of Vaud recognized the Armenian Genocide of 1915 in Ottoman Turkey<ref>{{cite web |url = http://www.panarmenian.net/eng/world/news/9255 |title = Swiss Canton of Vaud recognized the Armenian Genocide of 1915 in Ottoman Turkey |work = panarmenian.net |accessdate = June 2, 2016 }}</ref>\n\n;United Kingdom\nThe three devolved legislatures of the United Kingdom have recognised the Armenian Genocide.<ref name=\"theguardian.com\">{{cite news|author=David Leigh |url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2009/nov/03/armenia-genocide-denial-britain |title=Britain accused of 'genocide denial' over Armenia &#124; World news |newspaper=The Guardian |accessdate=2017-12-14}}</ref>\n\n* {{flag|Northern Ireland}}<ref>{{cite web |url = http://news.am/eng/news/12175.html |title = Scotland, North Ireland and Wales recognize Armenian Genocide |publisher = News.am |accessdate = June 2, 2016 }}</ref>\n* {{flag|Scotland}}<ref>{{cite web |url = http://news.am/eng/news/155362.html |title = Parliament of Scotland passes motion on Armenian Genocide |publisher = News.am |accessdate = June 2, 2016 }}</ref>\n* {{flag|Wales}}<ref>{{cite web |url = http://eafjd.eu/spip.php?breve2353 |title = First Minister of Wales recognises the Armenian Genocide on Holocaust Memorial Day \u2013 European Armenian Federation |publisher = Eafjd.eu |access-date = March 15, 2010 |archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20110720160053/http://eafjd.eu/spip.php?breve2353 |archive-date = July 20, 2011 |url-status = dead |df = mdy-all }}</ref>\n* {{flag|England}} The [[Derby City Council]] representing the city of [[Derby]], has recognised the Armenian Genocide in 2018 <ref name=\":2\" />\n\n;United States\n* {{flag|United States}}: 49 U.S.&nbsp;states have recognized the Armenian Genocide as of 2019.<ref name=\"ReferenceA\">{{cite news|url=https://armenianweekly.com/2019/03/20/alabama-becomes-49th-u-s-state-to-recognize-the-armenian-genocide|title=Alabama Becomes 49th U.S. State to Recognize the Armenian Genocide|work=[[Armenian Weekly]]|date=March 20, 2019}}</ref><ref name=usast>The number of states in the United States recognising the Armenian Genocide. Mississippi is the only U.S. state that has not yet officially memorialized and condemned the Armenian Genocide.[http://www.armenian-genocide.org/current_category.11/affirmation_list.html Armenian National Institute], [http://www.armenian-genocide.org/copyright.html Armenian National Institute, Inc.]</ref> On 27 November 2019, the [[District of Columbia]] of the United States adopted a resolution  recognizing the Armenian Genocide.<ref>{{cite web |url = https://armenpress.am/eng/news/996717.html |title = District of Columbia Council passes Armenian Genocide recognition resolution |publisher = Armenpress.am |accessdate = November 27, 2019 }}</ref>\n\n[[File:2016-04-24. \u041e\u0442\u043a\u0440\u044b\u0442\u0438\u0435 \u0445\u0430\u0447\u043a\u0430\u0440\u0430 \u0432 \u0414\u043e\u043d\u0435\u0446\u043a\u0435 004 (26789946732).jpg|thumb|Armenian Genocide Remembrance Day in [[Donetsk]], [[Ukraine]], 2016]]\n;Other\n* [[File:Flag of Quind\u00edo.svg|25px]] [[Quind\u00edo]], [[Colombia]]: The department's current capital city, formerly named \"Villa Holgu\u00edn\" at its foundation act in 1889, was after renamed [[Armenia, Quind\u00edo|Armenia]] as tribute to the genocide victims.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.guiaturisticadelquindio.com/historia-del-quindio |title=Historia del Quind\u00edo |publisher=Carlos A. Rodr\u00edguez O. |year=2013 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130313035504/http://www.guiaturisticadelquindio.com/historia-del-quindio |archivedate=March 13, 2013 }}</ref>\n* {{flag|Republic of Artsakh}}: The predominantly Armenian-populated region of [[Nagorno-Karabakh]] recognizes the Armenian Genocide.<ref>{{cite web |url = http://www.nkr.am/en/history-and-current-realities/79/ |title = History and Current Realities |work = nkr.am |accessdate = June 2, 2016 }}</ref> The self-proclaimed republic has declared April 24 as Genocide Memorial Day.<ref>{{cite web |url = http://www.nkrusa.org/country_profile/national_holidays.shtml |title = The Office of the Nagorno Karabakh Republic in USA |work = nkrusa.org |accessdate = June 2, 2016 }}</ref>\n* {{flag|Crimea}}: The Crimean Parliament recognized the Armenian Genocide in 2005.<ref>{{cite web |url = http://www.panarmenian.net/eng/world/news/13393 |title = Crimean supreme rada recognized armenian genocide |date = May 20, 2005 |work = Panarmenian.net }}</ref>\n\n=== Position of Turkey ===\nThe verdict of the [[Turkish courts-martial of 1919\u201320]] acknowledged the massacre of Armenians as \"war crimes\", and sentenced the perpetrators to death.<ref name=antos>{{cite news |last = Antos |first = Jason D. |title = Armenian Genocide Survivors Remember |url = http://www.qgazette.com/weekinreview/75979 |newspaper = The Queens Gazette |date = March 28, 2012 |quote = Only one Turkish government, under Damad Ferit Pasha, has ever recognized the Armenian Genocide. His administration held war crime trials and condemned most of the instigators to the massacre. Every other Turkish government has continued to deny the genocide. |access-date = April 28, 2015 |archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20170726153405/http://www.qgazette.com/weekinreview/75979 |archive-date = July 26, 2017 |url-status = dead }}</ref> However, in 1921, during the resurgence of the [[Turkish National Movement]], amnesty was given to those found guilty. Thereafter, the Turkish government, under [[Mustafa Kemal Atat\u00fcrk]], adopted a policy of denial.<ref name=antos /><ref name=huberta>{{cite book |last1 = v. Voss |first1 = Huberta |title = Portraits of Hope: Armenians in the Contemporary World |date = 2007 |publisher = Berghahn Books |isbn = 978-1-84545-257-5 |page = 293 |url = https://books.google.com/books?id=r3vbswx_1TEC }}</ref><ref>{{cite book |last1 = Cassese |first1 = Antonio |last2 = Acquaviva |first2 = Guido |last3 = Akande |first3 = Dapo |last4 = Baig |first4 = Laurel |last5 = Bing |first5 = Jia |last6 = Cryer |first6 = Robert |last7 = D\u00e9 |first7 = Urmila |title = The Oxford Companion to International Criminal Justice |date = 2009 |publisher = Oxford University Press |isbn = 978-0-19-102149-7 |pages = 898\u201399 |url = https://books.google.com/books?id=bHVCAgAAQBAJ }}</ref><ref>{{cite book |last1 = Eltringham |first1 = Nigel |last2 = Maclean |first2 = Pam |title = Remembering Genocide |date = 2014 |publisher = Routledge |isbn = 978-1-317-75422-0 |page = 41 |url = https://books.google.com/books?id=L-fpAwAAQBAJ }}</ref>\n\nA major obstacle for wider recognition of the genocide in the world is the official position of [[Turkey]], which states that there was no will to exterminate the Armenian population and the 1915 massacres were the consequences of [[Tehcir Law]] and [[World War I]].<ref>{{cite book |last = Totten |first = Samuel |title = Dictionary of Genocide: A-L |year = 2008 |publisher = Greenwood Press |location = Westport, Connecticut |isbn = 978-0-313-34642-2 |authorlink = Samuel Totten |author2 = Bartrop, Paul R. |authorlink2 = Paul R. Bartrop }}</ref>\n\nIn April 2006, the Turkish [[Human Rights Association (Turkey)|Human Rights Association]] recognized the events as a genocide.<ref>{{cite web |url = http://www.armenian-genocide.org/Affirmation.362/current_category.5/affirmation_detail.html |title = Human Rights Association of Turkey, Istanbul Branch |work = armenian-genocide.org |accessdate = June 2, 2016 }}</ref>\n\nIn December 2008, a group of Turkish intellectuals launched an online petition \u2013 named the \"[[I Apologize campaign|I Apologize]]\" campaign ('\u00d6z\u00fcr Diliyorum' in Turkish) \u2013 for people wanting to apologize in a personal capacity. The writers of the petition used the word \"the Great Catastrophe\" regarding the events. The petition gained upwards of 10,000 signatures in a matter of days. In the face of a backlash,<ref>{{cite news |url = http://zaman.com.tr/haber.do?haberno=771729&title=ermenilerden-ozur-dileyenler-tarih%EE-gercekleri-saptiriyor |archive-url = https://archive.today/20130419040717/http://zaman.com.tr/haber.do?haberno=771729&title=ermenilerden-ozur-dileyenler-tarih%EE-gercekleri-saptiriyor |url-status = dead |archive-date = April 19, 2013 |title = Ermenilerden \u00f6z\u00fcr dileyenler tarih\u00ee ger\u00e7ekleri sapt\u0131r\u0131yor |work = Zaman |language = Turkish |accessdate = June 2, 2016 }}</ref> then Turkish president [[Abdullah G\u00fcl]] defended the petition, citing freedom of speech.<ref>{{cite news |url = http://www.hurriyet.com.tr/english/domestic/10582943.asp |title = Turkish pres defends apology campaign to Armenians |date = December 16, 2008 |work = Hurriyet English }}</ref> An opposition group soon launched a Web site raising an even higher number of signatures. [[Recep Tayyip Erdogan]], at the time [[Prime Minister of Turkey|Prime Minister]], sided with the opposition, and a national debate ensued.<ref>{{cite news |url = http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/europe/7788486.stm |title = Turkish PM scorns Armenia apology |work = BBC News |date = December 17, 2008 }}</ref>\n\nSince the \"I Apologize\" campaign in 2008,{{fact|date=February 2020}} every year on April 24, commemoration ceremonies for the genocide are held in several Turkish cities.{{fact|date=February 2020}} They started at [[Taksim Square]] in [[Istanbul]] in 2008, mainly as a result of the nationwide discussion that came after the [[assassination of Hrant Dink]] and then spread to [[Ankara]], [[Diyarbak\u0131r]], [[\u0130zmir]], [[Malatya]], and [[Mersin]] in the following years.<ref>{{cite news |url = http://www.tert.am/en/news/2013/04/23/april-24-turkey/ |title = Turkish cities to host events in commemoration of Armenian Genocide victims, Apr 23, 24 |work = Tert Am |date = April 23, 2013 }}</ref> The commemorations draw increasing support each year.{{fact|date=February 2020}}\n\n[[Greens and the Left Party of the Future]] had announced that they recognized the Armenian Genocide in 2014.<ref>{{cite web |url = http://armenpress.am/eng/news/783523/turkey%E2%80%99s-green-party-recognizes-armenian-genocide.html |title = Turkey's Green Party recognizes Armenian Genocide &#124; ARMENPRESS Armenian News Agency |publisher = Armenpress.am |date =  |accessdate = April 23, 2015 }}</ref>\n\n=== Position of the United States ===\n{{further|United States resolution on Armenian Genocide}} \n[[File:US states that recognized Armenian Genocide.svg|thumbnail|right|U.S. states that recognize the Armenian Genocide]]\n[[File:Armenian genocide massive march in LA.JPG|thumb|[[Armenian Genocide Remembrance Day]] in [[Los Angeles]], [[California]], 2015]]\n\nIn 1951, the [[United States Department of State]] did actually exemplify the Armenian case as one of the committed acts of genocide in recent past. This view is evident in the written statement by United States given to the [[International Court of Justice]] (ICJ) that year, observing that: \"The Genocide Convention resulted from the inhuman and barbarous practices which prevailed in certain countries prior to and during World War II, when entire religious, racial and national minority groups were threatened with and subjected to deliberate extermination. The practice of genocide has occurred throughout human history. The [[Persecution of Christians in the Roman Empire|Roman persecution of the Christians]], the Turkish massacres of Armenians, the extermination of millions of Jews and Poles by the Nazis are outstanding examples of the crime of genocide. This was the background when the General Assembly of the United Nations considered the problem of genocide.\"<ref name=\"US-ICJ1951\">{{cite web|title=US Advisory Opinion to International Court of Justice|url= https://www.icj-cij.org/files/case-related/12/11767.pdf|publisher=icj.org|page=25}}</ref> That the USA later dramatically changed this position and has since consistently refrained from officially use the term \"genocide\" about the WWI events can be ascribed to the rise of the Cold War era and Turkey's NATO membership along with the disappearance of [[Raphael Lemkin]] as a strong human rights advocate from the ranks of the US State Department.<ref name=\"Avedian2018\">{{cite book | last=Avedian | first=Vahagn | title=Knowledge and Acknowledgement in the Politics of Memory of the Armenian Genocide | url=https://books.google.se/books?id=Tv7iuQEACAAJ | year=2018|publisher=Routledge|isbn=978-1-13-831885-4}} {{rp|83\u20134}}</ref>\n\nSeveral official U.S. documents describe the events as genocide. The [[United States House of Representatives]] adopted resolutions commemorating the Armenian Genocide in 1975,<ref name=\"Portraits of hope\">{{cite book |last = Von Voss |first = Huberta |title = Portraits of hope: Armenians in the contemporary world |publisher = Bergahn Books |year = 2007 |page = 36 |isbn = 978-1-84545-257-5 }}</ref><ref name=gov>[https://www.govtrack.us/congress/bills/94/hjres148/summary Summaries for Joint resolution to designate April 24, 1975, as National Day of Remembrance of Man's Inhumanity to Man.] U.S. House Joint Resolution 148, 94th Congress (1975\u20131976).</ref> 1984<ref>{{cite web |url = http://www.armenian-genocide.org/Affirmation.158/current_category.7/affirmation_detail.html |title = U.S. House of Representatives Joint Resolution 247 |publisher = Armenian-genocide.org |accessdate = June 2, 2016 }}</ref> and 1996.<ref>{{cite web |url = http://www.armenian-genocide.org/Affirmation.159/current_category.7/affirmation_detail.html |title = U.S. House of Representatives Resolution 3540 |publisher = Armenian-genocide.org |accessdate = June 2, 2016 }}</ref> President [[Ronald Reagan]] also described the events as genocide in his speech on April 22, 1981.<ref>{{cite web |url = http://www.armenian-genocide.org/Affirmation.63/current_category.4/affirmation_detail.html |title = Ronald Reagan, Proclamation, 22 April 1981 |publisher = Armenian-genocide.org |date = April 22, 1981 }}</ref> The legislatures of 49 out of the 50 U.S.&nbsp;states have made individual proclamations recognising the events of 1915 to 1923 as genocide.<ref name=usast /><ref name=\"The Armenians of Cyprus\">{{cite book|title=The Armenians of Cyprus|last=Hadjilyra|first=Alexander-Michael|publisher=Kalaydjian Foundation|year=2009|page=32}}</ref> As of March 4, 2010, the [[United States House Committee on Foreign Affairs]] has recognized the massacres of 1915 as genocide.<ref>{{cite news |title = U.S. House panel approves Armenia genocide resolution |url = http://news.xinhuanet.com/english2010/world/2010-03/05/c_13197636.htm |agency = Xinhua |date = May 3, 2010 }}</ref>\n\nThe United States government first acknowledged the Armenian Genocide back in 1951, in a document it submitted to the International Court of Justice, commonly known as the World Court.<ref name=unicj />\n\n{{quote|House Joint Resolution 148, adopted on April 8, 1975, resolved: \"Authorizes the President to designate April 24, 1975, as 'National Day of Remembrance of Man's Inhumanity to Man' for remembrance of all the victims of genocide, especially those of Armenian ancestry who succumbed to the genocide perpetrated in 1915.\"<ref name=gov />}}\n\nAfter the tenure of Ronald Reagan, later United States Presidents have refused to name the events as such because of concerns over alienating Turkey.<ref name=\"auto\">[https://news.yahoo.com/s/ap/20071010/ap_on_go_co/us_armenia_genocide Bush opposes Armenian genocide measure] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20071012021808/http://news.yahoo.com/s/ap/20071010/ap_on_go_co/us_armenia_genocide |date=October 12, 2007 }}, Desmond Butler, ''[[Associated Press]]'', October 10, 2007</ref>\n\nThe [[Armenian Assembly of America]] (AAA) and the [[Armenian National Committee of America]] (ANCA), advocacy organizations representing the views and values of the Armenian American community in the United States, have been urging Congress and the President of the United States to recognize the genocide by Ottoman Turkey in 1915.<ref name=\"Cameron, Fraser pp.91\">Cameron, Fraser ''United States foreign policy after the Cold War'' The Armenian-American\u00b4lobby, Routledge 2002 p. 91</ref> They have also asked for an increase of economic aid to Armenia.\n\nThe U.S. House Committee on Foreign Affairs approved [[United States resolution on Armenian Genocide|HR 106]], a bill that categorized and condemned the Ottoman Empire for the Genocide, on October 10, 2007, by a 27\u201321 vote. However, some of the support for the bill from both Democrats and Republicans eroded after the [[White House]] warned against the possibility of Turkey restricting [[airspace]] as well as ground-route access for U.S.&nbsp;military and humanitarian efforts in [[Iraq]] in response to the bill.<ref name=\"auto\" />  In response to the House Foreign Affairs Committee's decision on the bill, Turkey ordered their ambassador to the United States to return to Turkey for \"consultations\".<ref name=\"foxnews.com\">[http://www.foxnews.com/story/0,2933,301221,00.html Turkey Recalls Ambassador to U.S. Over Armenian Genocide Bill] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110629065759/http://www.foxnews.com/story/0,2933,301221,00.html |date=June 29, 2011 }}, ''[[Associated Press]]'', October 11, 2007.</ref>  The [[Turkish lobby]] worked intensely to block the bill's passage.<ref name=\"foxnews.com\" />\n\nOn January 19, 2008 United States Senator [[Barack Obama]] released a statement:\n\n{{quote|Two years ago, I criticized the Secretary of State for the firing of U.S.&nbsp;Ambassador to Armenia, [[John Marshall Evans|John Evans]], after he properly used the term genocide to describe Turkey's slaughter of thousands of Armenians starting in 1915. I shared with [[Condoleezza Rice|Secretary Rice]] my firmly held conviction that the Armenian Genocide is not an allegation, a personal opinion, or a point of view, but rather a widely documented fact supported by an overwhelming body of historical evidence. The facts are undeniable. An official policy that calls on diplomats to distort the historical facts is an untenable policy. As a senator, I strongly support passage of the Armenian Genocide Resolution (H.Res.106 and S.Res.106), and as President I will recognize the Armenian Genocide.<ref>{{cite web |url = http://www.barackobama.com/2008/01/19/barack_obama_on_the_importance.php |date = January 19, 2008 |accessdate = February 16, 2009 |title = Barack Obama on the Importance of US-Armenia Relations |publisher = barackobama.com |archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20090220125958/http://www.barackobama.com/2008/01/19/barack_obama_on_the_importance.php |archivedate = February 20, 2009 |url-status = dead |df = mdy-all }}</ref>}}\n\nAfter becoming president he retreated from those statements, stating only that his opinion had not changed but refused to use the word genocide. Despite his previous public recognition and support of genocide bills, as well as the election campaign promises to formally recognize the Armenian Genocide,<ref>{{cite news |title = Barack Obama on the Importance of US-Armenia Relations |url = http://www.barackobama.com/2008/01/19/barack_obama_on_the_importance.php |accessdate = April 26, 2010 |archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20100424170850/http://www.barackobama.com/2008/01/19/barack_obama_on_the_importance.php |archivedate = April 24, 2010 |url-status = dead |df = mdy-all }}</ref> Obama abstained from using the term \"genocide\".<ref>{{cite news |title = Barack Obama Campaign Promise No. 511 |url = http://www.politifact.com/truth-o-meter/promises/promise/511/recognize-armenian-genocide |accessdate = April 26, 2010 |archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20100506080622/http://www.politifact.com/truth-o-meter/promises/promise/511/recognize-armenian-genocide |archivedate = May 6, 2010  |url-status = live }}</ref> On April 24, 2009, he stated as president:\n\n{{quote|I have consistently stated my own view of what occurred in 1915, and my view of that history has not changed. My interest remains the achievement of a full, frank and just acknowledgment of the facts.<ref>{{cite web |url = http://www.whitehouse.gov/the_press_office/Statement-of-President-Barack-Obama-on-Armenian-Remembrance-Day/ |title = Statement of President Barack Obama on Armenian Remembrance Day, 2009 |publisher = Whitehouse.gov |date = 24 April 2009 |accessdate = 7 June 2012 }}</ref>}}\n\nOn April 24 commemoration speeches, Obama referred only to the Armenian synonym Mets Eghern (\"Mec E\u0121e\u1e59n\"). On April 24, 2010 Obama stated:\n\n{{quote|On this solemn day of remembrance, we pause to recall that ninety-five years ago one of the worst atrocities of the 20th&nbsp;century began. In that dark moment of history, 1.5&nbsp;million Armenians were massacred or marched to their death in the final days of the Ottoman Empire.\n\nToday is a day to reflect upon and draw lessons from these terrible events. I have consistently stated my own view of what occurred in 1915, and my view of that history has not changed. It is in all of our interest to see the achievement a full, frank and just acknowledgment of the facts. The Mets Yeghern is a devastating chapter in the history of the Armenian people, and we must keep its memory alive in honor of those who were murdered and so that we do not repeat the grave mistakes of the past.<ref>{{cite news |url = https://www.nytimes.com/2010/04/25/world/europe/25prexy.html |title = Obama Marks Genocide Without Saying the Word |date = 25 April 2010 |work = The New York Times |accessdate = 24 April 2016 }}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last = Poirier |first = John |url = https://www.reuters.com/article/idUSTRE63N1DX20100424 |title = Obama calls 1915 Armenia massacre an atrocity |work = Reuters |accessdate = June 7, 2012 }}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.todayszaman.com/tz-web/yazarDetay.do;jsessionid=BB087D1762D44E2FD55339250DD532D1?haberno=208482 |title=Today's Zaman \u2013 Meds Yeghern |publisher=Todayszaman.com |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090623213646/http://www.todayszaman.com/tz-web/yazarDetay.do |archivedate=June 23, 2009 }}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url = http://www.armenianweekly.com/2010/04/24/statement-of-president-barack-obama-on-armenian-remembrance-day-2/ |title = Statement of President Barack Obama on Armenian Remembrance Day |work= Armenian Weekly |date=April 24, 2010|accessdate = June 2, 2016 }}</ref>}}\n\nAlso in 2012,<ref>{{cite web |url = https://www.whitehouse.gov/the-press-office/2012/04/24/statement-president-armenian-remembrance-day |title = Statement by the President on Armenian Remembrance Day |work = whitehouse.gov |accessdate = June 2, 2016 }}</ref> 2013,<ref>{{cite web |url = https://www.whitehouse.gov/the-press-office/2013/04/24/statement-president-armenian-remembrance-day |title = Statement by the President on Armenian Remembrance Day |work = whitehouse.gov |accessdate = June 2, 2016 }}</ref> 2014<ref>{{cite web |url = https://www.whitehouse.gov/the-press-office/2014/04/24/statement-president-armenian-remembrance-day |title = Statement by the President on Armenian Remembrance Day |work = whitehouse.gov |accessdate = June 2, 2016 }}</ref> 2015,<ref>[[The Washington Post]]: [https://www.washingtonpost.com/blogs/post-politics/wp/2015/04/23/obama-marks-armenian-remembrance-day-without-using-genocide/ Obama's statement on Armenia avoids 'genocide']</ref><ref>T\u00fcrkisches Au\u00dfenministerium: [http://www.mfa.gov.tr/no_-131_-24-april-2015_-press-release-regarding-the-statement-made-by-us-president-obama-on-the-occasion-of-24-april.en.mfa Press release 131]</ref> and 2016<ref>{{cite news |title = Despite Campaign Vow, Obama Declines to Call Massacre of Armenians 'Genocide' |url = https://www.nytimes.com/2016/04/23/world/europe/despite-campaign-vow-obama-declines-to-call-massacre-of-armenians-genocide.html |accessdate = May 4, 2016 |work = The New York Times |date = April 22, 2016 }}</ref> he did not use the word 'genocide'.\nIn April 2015, Obama sent a Presidential Delegation to Armenia to attend the Centennial Commemoration in [[Yerevan]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://obamawhitehouse.archives.gov/the-press-office/2015/04/21/president-obama-announces-presidential-delegation-republic-armenia-atten|title=President Obama Announces Presidential Delegation to the Republic of Armenia to Attend the Centennial Commemoration of the Events of 1915|date=April 21, 2015|website=whitehouse.gov}}</ref>\n[[Susan E. Rice]], Obama's [[National Security Advisor (United States)|National Security Advisor]], encouraged the Foreign Minister [[Mevl\u00fct \u00c7avu\u015fo\u011flu]] of Turkey to take concrete steps to improve relations with Armenia and to facilitate an open and frank dialogue in Turkey about the atrocities of 1915.<ref>whitehouse.gov: [https://www.whitehouse.gov/the-press-office/2015/04/21/statement-nsc-spokesperson-bernadette-meehan-national-security-advisor-s Press release 21 April 2015]</ref>\n\nOn October 29, 2019, the [[United States House of Representatives]] passed a resolution on a 405\u201311 vote to recognize the Armenian genocide. The [[United States Senate]] passed the resolution through unanimous vote on December 12, 2019.<ref>{{cite web |url = https://www.theguardian.com/us-news/2019/dec/12/senate-armenian-genocide-vote-trump-turkey |title = US Senate defies Trump in unanimous vote to recognize Armenian genocide |work = theguardian.com |accessdate = December 12, 2019 }}</ref>\n\n=== Kurdish position ===\n{{further|Kurdish recognition of the Armenian Genocide}}\n\nSome Kurdish tribes played a role in the genocide, as they were an important tool used by the Ottoman authorities to carry out the killings.<ref>{{cite news |url = https://www.nytimes.com/1896/07/26/archives/many-christians-killed-turks-and-kurds-slaughter-armenians-around.html |work = The New York Times |title = Many Christians Killed; Kurds and Turks Slaughter Armenians Around Van. Nearly Three Thousand Men. Women, and Children Dead \u2013 Every Male over Eight Years of Age in Forty Villages Perishes \u2013 Graphic Account of the Horrible Massacre Given in Letters from an American Missionary |date = July 26, 1896 }}</ref>  Among modern Kurds, including major Kurdish parties like the [[Peoples' Democratic Party (Turkey)|Peoples' Democratic Party]] (HDP), and the [[Kurdistan Democratic Party]] (KDP), most of them acknowledge the killings and apologize in the name of their ancestors who committed atrocities toward Armenians and [[Assyrian people|Assyrians]] in the name of the Ottoman Empire.<ref>{{cite web |author = HULIQ |url = http://www.huliq.com/1/76745/important-kurdish-leader-turkey-apologizes-arameans |title = An important Kurdish Leader in Turkey apologizes to Arameans |publisher = HULIQ |accessdate = June 2, 2016 }}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url = http://www.a1plus.am/en/society/2005/05/13/14512 |title = Kurds Apologize to Armenians: The Armenian News by A1 |publisher = A1plus.am |date = June 1, 2012 }}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url = http://www.xoybun.com/modules.php?name=Content&pa=showpage&pid=674 |title = PDK-XOYBUN; wiha, di xizmeta, Kurd \u00fb Kurdistan\u00ea daye : Pirojeya Kurdistana Mezin, Pirojey\u00ean Abor\u00ee \u00fb Avakirin, Pirojey\u00ean Cand \u00fb Huner, L\u00eakol\u00eena D\u00eeroka Kurdistan\u00ea, Perwerdeya Ziman\u00ea Kurd\u00ee, Perwerdeya Zan\u00een \u00fb S\u00eeyas\u00ee, We\u015fana Malper \u00fb TV y\u00ean Kurdistane. - Content |publisher = Xoybun.com |date = March 9, 2004 |accessdate = April 23, 2015 }}</ref><ref name=\"hurriyet.com.tr\">{{cite web |url = http://www.hurriyet.com.tr/english/domestic/10672641.asp?scr=1 |title = Pro-Kurdish party leader apologizes to Armenians for 1915 incidents |publisher = Hurriyet.com.tr |date =  |accessdate = April 23, 2015 }}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url = http://kurdistantribune.com/2014/kurdish-question-cant-be-understood-ignoring-armenian-genocide/ |title = 'Kurdish question' can't be understood ignoring the Armenian genocide |publisher = The Kurdistan Tribune |date = May 1, 2014 |accessdate = April 23, 2015 }}</ref>\n\n=== Position of France ===\n[[File:Lyon - 24 April 2015.jpg|thumb|Armenian Genocide Remembrance Day in [[Lyon]], 2015]]\nFrance has formally recognized the Armenian massacres as genocide.<ref name=\"BBC\">[http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/102803.stm], May 29, 1998</ref>\n\nIn 2006, the [[French Parliament]] submitted a bill to create a law that would punish any person denying the Armenian Genocide with up to five years' imprisonment and a fine <ref name=\"France\">{{in lang|fr}} [http://www.assembleenationale.fr/12/propositions/pion3030.asp Proposition de loi compl\u00e9tant la loi n\u00b0 2001\u201370 du 29 janvier 2001 relative \u00e0 la reconnaissance du g\u00e9nocide arm\u00e9nien de 1915], [[National Assembly of France]], April 12, 2006: bill proposing that denying the Armenian genocide shall be punished likewise to [[Holocaust denial|the denial of the Jewish Holocaust]]</ref> Despite Turkish protests,<ref name=\"Turkey warns France over Armenian Genocide Bill\">{{cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2006/oct/11/turkey.eu|title=Turkey warns France over Armenian Genocide Bill|last=Chrisafis|first=Angelique|date=October 10, 2006|work=The Guardian}}</ref> the [[National Assembly of France|French National Assembly]] adopted a bill making it a crime to deny that Armenians suffered genocide in 1915 at the hands of the Ottoman Turks.<ref>{{in lang|fr}} [http://www.assemblee-nationale.fr/12/dossiers/reconnaissance_genocide_armenien_1915_loi_2001.asp legislative file] of the [[French National Assembly]]; [http://www.assemblee-nationale.fr/12/scrutins/jo1021.asp vote tally]</ref> The bill had been criticized as an attempt to garner votes from among the 600,000 ethnic Armenians of France.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/Europe/6045838.stm |title=Accusation of an attempt to garner votes |work=BBC News |accessdate=February 7, 2007 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20070207113656/http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/europe/6045838.stm |archivedate=February 7, 2007 |url-status=dead |df=mdy }}</ref> This criticism has come not only from within Turkey,<ref name=\"CBCFRENCHBILL\">{{cite news |publisher = [[CBC News]] |url = https://www.cbc.ca/news/world/french-politicians-pass-armenian-genocide-bill-1.572699 |title = French politicians pass Armenian genocide bill |date = October 12, 2006 }}</ref> but also from [[Orhan Pamuk]].<ref>{{in lang|tr}} [http://www.internethaber.com/news_detail.php?id=47327 Orhan Pamuk Fransa'yi kinadi] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20070927203740/http://www.internethaber.com/news_detail.php?id=47327 |date=September 27, 2007 }}, ''Internet Haber'', October 13, 2006</ref> However, the bill was dropped in the summer of 2011 before coming to the Senate.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.todayszaman.com/news-259860-sarkozy-in-bid-to-make-up-for-armenia-remarks-through-aide.html |title=Sarkozy in bid to make up for Armenia remarks through aide |publisher=Todayszaman.com |date=October 14, 2011 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20111015185125/http://www.todayszaman.com/news-259860-sarkozy-in-bid-to-make-up-for-armenia-remarks-through-aide.html |archivedate=October 15, 2011 }}</ref>\n\nSince then, France has urged Turkey to recognize the 1915 massacre as genocide.<ref>{{cite news |url = http://uk.reuters.com/article/2011/10/06/france-georgia-idUKL5E7L64CE20111006 |title = Sarkozy challenges Turkey to face its history |last = Jarry |first = Emmanual |date = October 6, 2011 |work = Reuters |accessdate = October 7, 2011 }}</ref>\n\nThe [[Senate (France)|French Senate]] passed a bill in 2011 that criminalizes denial of acknowledged genocides, which includes both the Holocaust and the Armenian Genocide. The bill was submitted by the parliament in 2012.<ref>[http://www.france24.com/en/20120123-french-senate-passes-bill-outlawing-genocide-denial-armenia-turkey French Senate passes bill outlawing genocide denial], [[France 24]], January 23, 2012.</ref> However, the bill was considered unconstitutional on February 28, 2012 by the [[Constitutional Council of France|French Constitutional Court]]: \"The council rules that by punishing anyone contesting the existence of... crimes that lawmakers themselves recognized or qualified as such, lawmakers committed an unconstitutional attack on freedom of expression\".<ref>[http://www.france24.com/en/20120228-france-turkey-genocide-armenia-sarkozy-freedom-expression French genocide law 'unconstitutional' rules court], ''[[France 24]]'', February 28, 2012</ref>\n\nThe French Senate adopted a new bill on October 14, 2016 that made the denial of the Armenian Genocide a crime. The bill was introduced by the French Government and passed by the French National Assembly in July 2016, and stipulates a penalty of a year in prison or a 45,000 Euro fine.<ref name=france/> However, the law was put down by the French Constitutional Court in January 2017. The Council said the \"ruling causes uncertainty regarding expressions and comments on historical matters. Thereby, this ruling is an unnecessary and disproportionate attack against freedom of speech.\"<ref>[http://asbarez.com/159545/french-court-rules-against-criminalization-of-genocide-denial/ French Court Rules Against Criminalization of Genocide Denial] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170220044447/http://asbarez.com/159545/french-court-rules-against-criminalization-of-genocide-denial/ |date=20 February 2017 }}.\n Asbarez. 27 January 2017.</ref>\n\nOn February 5, 2019, French President Emmanuel Macron declared April 24 as Armenian Genocide commemoration day in [[France]].<ref name=\"News.am\"/>\n\n=== Position of the United Kingdom ===\nThe [[Devolution in the United Kingdom|devolved legislatures]] of Northern Ireland, Scotland and Wales have all formally recognised the Armenian Genocide. The government of the United Kingdom does not recognize the Armenian Genocide, as it considers that the evidence is not clear enough to retrospectively consider \"the terrible events that afflicted the Ottoman Armenian population at the beginning of the last century\" to be genocide under the 1948 UN convention. The British government states the \"massacres were an appalling tragedy\" and condemns them stating that this was the view of the government during that period.<ref name=\"theguardian.com\"/> In 2000, an [[early day motion]] recognising the Armenian Genocide by the UK&nbsp;Parliament was signed by 185&nbsp;MPs.<ref>{{cite web |url = http://www.newstatesman.com/world-affairs/2007/10/armenian-genocide-turkey |title = Time to recognise the Armenian genocide, by Vahe Gabrielyan, New Statesman, 12 October 2007 |publisher = Newstatesman.com |accessdate = June 2, 2016 }}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url = http://www.panarmenian.net/news/eng/?nid=23853 |title = Over 200 British MPs recognise Armenian Genocide 25 October 2007 |publisher = Panarmenian.net }}</ref>\n\n[[File:Armenian memorial unveiled - geograph.org.uk - 778957.jpg|thumb|Armenian memorial unveiled in [[Cardiff]] in 2007]]\n\nHowever, in 2007, the position of the British government was that it condemns the massacres, but \"neither this Government nor previous British Governments have judged that the evidence is sufficiently unequivocal to persuade us that these events should be categorised as genocide as defined by the [[Convention on the Prevention and Punishment of the Crime of Genocide|1948 UN&nbsp;Convention on Genocide]], a convention which is, in any event, not retrospective in application.\"<ref>{{cite news |url = http://www.pm.gov.uk/output/Page13999.asp |title = Armeniangenocide \u2013 epetition Government's response; |date = December 7, 2007 |archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20071217025520/http://www.pm.gov.uk/output/Page13999.asp |archive-date = December 17, 2007 }}</ref> In 2009, the lawyer [[Geoffrey Robertson]] QC revealed in a disclosure of Foreign Office documents entitled ''\"Was there an Armenian Genocide?\"'',<ref name=Geoffrey>[[Geoffrey Robertson]] QC: [http://www.doughtystreet.co.uk/files/Armenian%20genocide1.pdf \"Was there an Armenian Genocide?\"] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100326220751/http://www.doughtystreet.co.uk/files/Armenian%20genocide1.pdf |date=March 26, 2010 }}. October 9, 2009.</ref> how the British Parliament has routinely been misinformed and misled by ministers who have recited [[Foreign and Commonwealth Office|FCO]] briefs without questioning their accuracy. As summarized by Robertson, \"there was no 'evidence' that had ever been looked at and there had never been a 'judgment' at all.\"<ref>{{cite web |title = A genocide denied |url = http://www.newstatesman.com/law-and-reform/2009/12/foreign-office-genocide |website = www.newstatesman.com |accessdate = April 24, 2015 }}</ref> A 1999 Foreign Office briefing for ministers said that the recognition of the Armenian Genocide would provide no practical benefit to the UK and goes on to say that ''\"The current line is the only feasible option\" owing to \"the importance of our relations (political, strategic and commercial) with Turkey\"''. The Foreign Office documents furthermore include advice from 1995 to the then Conservative foreign minister, [[Douglas Hogg]], that he should refuse to attend a memorial service for the victims of the genocide.<ref>[https://www.theguardian.com/world/2009/nov/03/armenia-genocide-denial-britain Britain accused of 'genocide denial' over Armenia]. [[The Guardian]]. November 3, 2009. Retrieved January 13, 2013</ref> As of 2015, the United Kingdom does not formally recognise the Ottoman Empire's massacres of Armenians as a \"genocide\".<ref>{{cite news |url= https://www.theguardian.com/world/on-the-middle-east/2015/apr/23/britain-sidesteps-armenian-genocide-recognition-a-century-after-killings |title=Britain sidesteps Armenian genocide recognition a century after killings |newspaper=The Guardian |date=23 April 2015 }}</ref>\n\n[[James Bryce, 1st Viscount Bryce|James Bryce]] (1838\u20131922), 1st Viscount Bryce, was one of the first Britons to bring this issue to public attention.<ref name=\"Travis\">Travis, Hannibal. \"[http://papers.ssrn.com/sol3/papers.cfm?abstract_id=1809090 Genocide in the Middle East: The Ottoman Empire, Iraq, and Sudan].\" Durham, NC: ''Carolina Academic Press'', 2010, 2007, pp. 237\u201377, 293\u2013294.</ref><ref name=\"Travis2\">Travis, Hannibal. \"[http://utpjournals.metapress.com/content/yv544142p5rnx055/?p=91e7dbe895ec4cbf9eef0ad842fef76a&pi=6 'Native Christians Massacred': The Ottoman Genocide of the Assyrians During World War I] {{webarchive|url=https://archive.today/20120716033637/http://utpjournals.metapress.com/content/yv544142p5rnx055/?p=91e7dbe895ec4cbf9eef0ad842fef76a&pi=6 |date=16 July 2012 }}.\" ''Genocide Studies and Prevention'', Vol. 1, No. 3, December 2006, pp. 327\u2013371. Retrieved 2 February 2010.</ref>\n\n=== Position of Australia ===\n[[Australia]] does not view the events at the end of the [[Ottoman Empire]] as a genocide.<ref name=\"ata-a.org.au\"/> Australia is one of the countries who were at war with the Ottoman Empire at the time of the events, notably during the [[Gallipoli Campaign]]. Australia does acknowledge the tragic events had devastating effects on the identity, heritage, and culture of all the people in the areas that the events have occurred. Furthermore, in response to the motions of [[New South Wales]] and [[South Australia]] to recognize the events as genocide the Foreign Minister of Australia has clarified on June 4, 2014, that Australian states and territories have no constitutional role in the formulation of the Australian foreign policy, and that Australia does not view the tragic events at the end of the Ottoman Empire as a genocide.<ref name=\"ata-a.org.au\">{{cite web |title = 100 Years on, Australia's still out of Step on the Armenian Genocide|url = http://www.internationalaffairs.org.au/australianoutlook/100-years-on-australias-still-out-of-step-on-the-armenian-genocide/|publisher = International Affairs |date = April 24, 2015 }}</ref>\n\n=== Position of Israel ===\nOfficially Israel neither recognizes nor denies the Armenian Genocide. This stems from a few geopolitical considerations. First, according to ''[[The Times of Israel]]'', \"Israel is a small country in a hostile neighborhood that can't afford to antagonize the few friends it has in the region. Even more powerful states refuse to employ the 'genocide' term for fear of alienating Turkey....\"<ref name=Ahren>Raphael Ahren, [http://www.timesofisrael.com/why-israel-still-refuses-to-recognize-a-century-old-genocide/ Why Israel still refuses to recognize a century-old genocide], Times of Israel, April 24, 2015</ref> Second, Israel shares a \"budding friendship\" with Azerbaijan, a \"Shiite Muslim but moderate country bordering Iran\" that also strongly opposes recognition.<ref name=Ahren /> Third, according to former Israeli minister [[Yossi Sarid]] (one of the country's most vocal supporters of Armenian Genocide recognition), Israel tends to follow policies set by the United States, which had not recognized it.<ref name=Heller>Aron Heller, [http://www.timesofisrael.com/israel-grapples-with-whether-to-recognize-armenian-genocide/ Israel grapples with question of Armenian genocide recognition], Associated Press, April 23, 2015</ref> Despite these concerns, many prominent Israeli figures from different sides of the political spectrum have called for recognition.<ref name=Ahren /><ref name=Heller />\n\nIn 2003, the Catholicos of All Armenian [[Karekin II]] visited the then [[Ashkenazi Chief Rabbi of Israel]] [[Yona Metzger]] who accepted an invitation by Karekin II to visit Armenia,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.armeniandiaspora.com/forum/showthread.php?t=26904 |title=www.armeniandiaspora.com/forum/showthread.php?t=26904 |work=armeniandiaspora.com |accessdate=June 2, 2016 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20070927184444/http://www.armeniandiaspora.com/forum/showthread.php?t=26904 |archivedate=September 27, 2007 }}</ref> a trip that he made in 2005, including a visit to the [[Tsitsernakaberd]] (the Genocide Memorial in [[Yerevan]]).<ref name=\"armenianchurch.org\">{{cite web |url = http://www.armenianchurch.org/index.jsp?sid=3&nid=421&y=2005&m=10&d=22&lng=en |title = The Armenian Church |work = armenianchurch.org |accessdate = June 2, 2016 }}</ref> While doing so he formally recognised the Armenian Genocide as a historical fact.<ref name=\"ym\">{{cite web |title = World Jewish Congress: Israeli Chief Rabbi says killing of Armenians in 1915 was genocide |url = http://www.worldjewishcongress.org/en/news/5737/israeli_chief_rabbi_says_killing_of_armenians_in_1915_was_genocide }}</ref>\n\nIsrael appeared to move closer to officially recognizing the genocide in 2011 when the [[Knesset]] held its first open discussion on the matter. By a unanimous vote of 20\u20130, the Knesset approved referring the subject to the Education Committee for more extensive deliberation.<ref>{{cite news |last = Stoil |first = Rebecca Anna |title = Knesset moves toward recognizing Armenian genocide |url = http://www.jpost.com/DiplomacyAndPolitics/Article.aspx?id=221187 |accessdate = May 19, 2011 |newspaper = [[Jerusalem Post]] |date = May 18, 2011 |quote = For years, consecutive governments had blocked attempts by MKs to raise the subject of recognizing the genocide out of concern that such recognition could damage relations with Ankara. This year, however, the government did not block the hearing. }}</ref> Israel's [[List of Knesset speakers|speaker of the Knesset]] told an Israel-based Armenian action committee that he intended to introduce an annual parliamentary session to mark the genocide.<ref>{{cite news |last = Lis |first = Jonathan |title = Knesset Speaker working to boost recognition of Armenian genocide |url = http://www.haaretz.com/print-edition/news/knesset-speaker-working-to-boost-recognition-of-armenian-genocide-1.365034 |accessdate = June 2, 2011 |newspaper = [[Haaretz]] |date = May 31, 2011 |quote = Knesset Speaker Reuven Rivlin said Monday that he wanted to convene an annual parliamentary session of the full Knesset to mark the Armenian genocide of 1915 and 1916 at the hands of the Turks. 'It is my duty as a Jew and Israeli to recognize the tragedies of other peoples,' Rivlin said, speaking to an Israel-based Armenian action committee. }}</ref> A special parliamentary session held in 2012 to determine if Israel would recognize the Armenian Genocide ended inconclusively. Then\u2013Knesset Speaker [[Reuven Rivlin]] and Cabinet Minister [[Gilad Erdan]] were among those supporting formal recognition by the government.<ref>{{cite news |title = Israeli minister calls to recognize Armenian genocide |url = https://www.reuters.com/article/2012/06/12/us-israel-turkey-armenians-idUSBRE85B16320120612 |accessdate = June 13, 2012 |agency = [[Reuters]] |date = June 12, 2012 }}</ref> The recognition was not approved at that time and in 2015, [[Rafael Harpaz]], Israel's ambassador to [[Azerbaijan]], said in an interview that Foreign Minister [[Avigdor Lieberman]] has made it clear that Israel will not recognize the Armenian Genocide, given Israel's hopes that its political and economic relationship with Turkey can improve.<ref>[http://www.haaretz.com/news/diplomacy-defense/1.636058 Israel won't recognize Armenian genocide, says ambassador] ''Haaretz'', January 9, 2015</ref> Another great concern is Azerbaijan, which is Israel's main oil supplier, a buyer of Israeli arms, and a Muslim ally in the global coalition against Iran.<ref name=Patriarch>Nir Hasson, [http://www.haaretz.com/news/features/.premium-1.654015 Armenian Patriarch 'disappointed' in Israeli policy on Armenian genocide], Haaretz, April 28, 2015</ref>\n\n[[Member of Knesset|MKs]] supporting recognition have acknowledged the effect it could have on [[Azerbaijan\u2013Israel relations|Israel\u2013Azerbaijan]] and [[Israel\u2013Turkey relations]]. As then Knesset Spokesperson Rivlin said, \"Turkey is and will be an ally of Israel. The talks with Turkey are understandable and even necessary from a strategic and diplomatic perspective. But those circumstances cannot justify the Knesset ignoring the tragedy of another people\" and [[Ayelet Shaked]] (of the religious-nationalist [[Jewish Home]] party) said: \"We must confront our silence and that of the world in the face of such horrors.\"<ref name=haaretz517200>{{cite web |url = http://www.haaretz.com/news/diplomacy-defense/in-israel-both-coalition-and-opposition-urge-remembrance-of-armenian-genocide.premium-1.517200 |title = In Israel, both coalition and opposition urge remembrance of Armenian genocide |author = Jonathan Lis |date = April 23, 2013 |work = Haaretz.com }}</ref><ref name=Ynetnews>Moran Azulay, [http://www.ynetnews.com/articles/0,7340,L-4371664,00.html Knesset discusses Armenian Genocide], Ynetnews, April 24, 2013</ref> In 2000, then\u2013education minister [[Yossi Sarid]], chairman of the dovish [[Meretz]] party, announced plans to place the Armenian Genocide on Israel's history curricula.<ref name=Ahren /> As a result of Sarid's 2000 speech to an Armenian church in Jerusalem recognizing their genocide, he became [[persona non grata]] in Turkey.<ref name=Heller /> Meretz has long fought for recognition of the genocide.<ref name=Patriarch /> [[Zehava Galon]], a successor of Sarid as Meretz leader, has initiated several motions in the Knesset calling for the government to recognize the Armenian Genocide. In 2013 she said, \"Reconciliation with Turkey is an important and strategic move, but it should not affect the recognition.\"<ref name=Ynetnews /> Her 2014 motion also enjoyed much support on the Knesset floor, including that of Knesset Speaker [[Yuli Edelstein]].<ref name=\"autogenerated1\">Lahav Harkov, [http://www.jpost.com/Middle-East/Knesset-Speaker-Recognizing-Armenian-genocide-is-a-moral-imperative-for-Jews-352169 'Recognizing Armenian genocide is a moral imperative for Jews'], Jerusalem Post, March 13, 2014</ref> Galon has also paid her respects at local Armenian memorial services.<ref>Elhanan Miller, [http://www.timesofisrael.com/citing-holocaust-israeli-armenians-demand-genocide-recognition/ Citing Holocaust, Israeli Armenians demand genocide recognition], Times of Israel, April 26, 2015</ref>\n\nRivlin, now [[president of Israel]], was one of the Knesset's most outspoken proponents of recognition. It was reported in 2014 that due to the sensitivities of Israel's relationship with Turkey, Rivlin was quietly distancing himself from the Israeli campaign to recognize the Armenian Genocide and chose not to sign the annual petition, which he had previously done.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.timesofisrael.com/rivlin-backtracks-on-armenian-genocide-recognition/|title=Rivlin backtracks on Armenian genocide recognition|first=Tamar|last=Pileggi|website=www.timesofisrael.com}}</ref> Still, Israel has taken greater steps toward Armenian Genocide recognition under Rivlin's presidency. Rivlin was the first Israeli president to speak at the United Nations on the issue.<ref name=Term>Raphael Ahren, [http://www.timesofisrael.com/rivlin-used-term-armenian-genocide-two-weeks-ago/ Rivlin used term 'Armenian genocide' two weeks ago], ''Times of Israel'', April 28, 2015</ref> During the [[United Nations Holocaust Memorial]] on January 28, 2015, President Rivlin spoke about the Armenian tragedy.<ref>{{cite web |url = http://armenianweekly.com/2015/02/11/auron/ |title = Sassounian: Auron Blasts Israel's President for Calling 'Armenian Genocide' a Massacre |author= Harut Sassounian|work = Armenian Weekly |date=February 11, 2015 |accessdate = June 2, 2016 }}</ref> It was observed that in his speech he used the phrase \u05e8\u05e6\u05d7 \u05d1\u05e0\u05d9 \u05d4\u05e2\u05dd \u05d4\u05d0\u05e8\u05de\u05e0\u05d9 ''re\u1e93a\u1e25 bnei ha\u02bfam haArmeni'', which means \"the murder of the members of the Armenian nation,\" coming close to the Hebrew term for genocide, \u05e8\u05e6\u05d7 \u05e2\u05dd ''re\u1e93a\u1e25 \u02bfam''.<ref name=Skirts>Adiv Sterman, [http://www.timesofisrael.com/in-marking-armenian-tragedy-rivlin-skirts-term-genocide/ In marking Armenian tragedy, Rivlin skirts term 'genocide'] Times of Israel, April 26, 2015</ref> In addition, 2015 marked the first time that Israel sent a delegation\u2014[[Nachman Shai]] (Zionist Union) and [[Anat Berko]] (Likud)\u2014to [[Yerevan]] for the official memorial event. In an event billed as the first to be held by an Israeli president to commemorate the tragedy, Rivlin also invited Armenian communal and religious leader's to his official residence on April 26, 2015. He said we are \"morally obligated to point out the facts, as horrible as they might be, we must not ignore them.\" As he skirted using the term \"genocide,\" some Armenian leaders were disappointed, though still thankful for the event.<ref name=Skirts /> However, it was later reported that earlier that same month, while briefing foreign journalists in English, Rivlin had in fact referred to the killings as genocide, saying: <blockquote>It was [[Avshalom Feinberg]], one of my eldest brothers, who said 25 years before the Holocaust that if we do not warn against what is going on with the Armenians, what will happen afterwards when they try to do to us\u2026? There is a saying that the Nazis used the Armenian genocide as something that gave them permission to bring the Holocaust into reality, according to their belief that they have to discriminate against the Jewish people. 'Never again' belongs to every one of you, all the nations. We cannot allow something like that to happen.\"<ref name=Term /></blockquote>\n\nIn 2015, a group of distinguished Israeli academics, artists, and former generals and politicians signed a [http://www.combatgenocide.org/il/?page_id=4215 petition] calling on Israel to follow the Pope's lead and recognize the genocide.<ref name=Heller /> The signatories included author [[Amos Oz]], historian [[Yehuda Bauer]], Major General (ret.) [[Amos Yadlin]], former Likud minister [[Dan Meridor]] and about a dozen former MKs and ministers.<ref name=Ahren />\n\nIsraeli President [[Reuven Rivlin]] visited the [[Armenian Patriarchate of Jerusalem]] on May 9, 2016. Concluding his speech he said, that \"the Armenians were massacred in 1915. My parents remember thousands of Armenian migrants finding asylum at the Armenian Church. No one in Israel denies that an entire nation was massacred.\"<ref>{{cite web |url = http://www.mediamax.am/en/news/society/18195/ |title = No one denies the massacre of Armenians, says President of Israel |author =  |date =  |work = mediamax.am |accessdate = June 2, 2016 }}</ref>\n\nOn August 1, 2016, the [[Knesset Committee on Education, Culture and Sports]] recognized the Armenian Genocide.<ref>[https://www.knesset.gov.il/spokesman/eng/PR_eng.asp?PRID=12199 Knesset News]</ref>\n\n=== Position of other countries ===\n[[File:Armenian Heritage Park.jpg|thumb|left|The Armenian Heritage Park in downtown [[Boston]]]]\n\n[[File:Larnaca monument.jpg|thumb|Armenian genocide monument in [[Larnaca]], Cyprus. Cyprus was among the first countries to recognize the genocide.]]\n\n[[Azerbaijan]], which is in a strategic alliance with Turkey and is in conflict with [[Armenia]] because of the [[Nagorno-Karabakh War]], shares the position of Turkey. During the Communist rule, when Azerbaijan was a part of the USSR, a brief description of the Armenian Genocide was placed in the ''[[Azerbaijani Soviet Encyclopedia]]''.<ref>[Azerbaijani Soviet Encyclopedia, Vol. IV, Baku, 1980, p. 84]</ref>\n\nThe [[Ukraine|Ukrainian]] town [[Izyum]] recognized the killings as genocide on New Year's Eve 2009 but after lobbying by the [[Azeris in Ukraine|Azerbaijani community]] of [[Crimea]], their city council canceled that decision on April 1, 2010. This is the first case in the world when the decision on a recognition was cancelled.<ref>[http://en.apa.az/news.php?id=118955 Izyum City Council cancels its decision on recognition of so-called Armenian genocide]{{Unreliable source?|date=March 2012}} {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120325184359/http://en.apa.az/news.php?id=118955 |date=March 25, 2012 }}, [[Azerbaijan Press Agency]] (April 1, 2010)</ref>\n\n[[Denmark]] believes (2008) that the genocide recognition should be discussed by historians, not politicians.<ref>{{cite news |url = http://www.haaba.com/tags/turkey?q=node/73680 |title = Denmark does not recognize Armenian genocide: minister |date = January 10, 2008 |agency = AFP }}</ref> However, on January 26, 2017 the Danish Parliament adopted a resolution regarding the Armenian Genocide, which recognizes the \"tragic and bloody events that took place in eastern Anatolia in the period 1915\u20131923\".<ref name=\":0\">{{cite web|author=Hairenik |url=http://armenianweekly.com/2017/01/26/danish-parliament-2017-bill-armenian-genocide/ |title=Danish Parliament Passes Questionable Bill Regarding Armenian Genocide |work=Armenian Weekly |date=January 26, 2017|accessdate=2017-12-14}}</ref>\n\nIn [[Bulgaria]], activists first tried to persuade the parliament to acknowledge the genocide in 2008, but the proposal was voted down.<ref>{{cite news |url = http://www.panarmenian.net/news/eng/?nid=17162 |title = Bulgarian Parliament Rejected Armenian Genocide Recognition Bill |date = January 10, 2008 }}</ref> Shortly after the decision of the parliament, several of the biggest municipalities in Bulgaria accepted a resolution recognising the genocide.<ref>{{cite news |url = http://www.novinite.com/view_news.php?id=92690 |title = Bulgaria's Dobrich Recognizes Armenian Genocide |date = May 27, 2009 }}</ref> The resolution was first passed in [[Plovdiv]] followed by [[Burgas]], [[Ruse, Bulgaria|Ruse]], [[Stara Zagora]], [[Pazardzhik]] and others. In 2015, however, the [[National Assembly (Bulgaria)|Bulgarian parliament]] adopted a declaration recognising the \"mass extermination of the Armenian People in the Ottoman Empire\" in the period 1915\u20131922, but did not use the word \"genocide\".<ref name=\"standartnews.com\" /><ref>[[Ministry of Foreign Affairs (Turkey)]]: [http://www.mfa.gov.tr/no_-134_-25-april-2015_-press-release-regarding-on-the-decision-adopted-by-the-bulgarian-parliament-regarding-the-events-of-1915.en.mfa Press Release Regarding the Decision Adopted by the Bulgarian Parliament Regarding the Events of 1915]</ref>\n\n{{clear}}\n\n== The Armenian diaspora and the genocide's recognition ==\n[[File:Armenian Genocide Memorial, Armenian Church, Kolkata.jpg|thumb|Armenian Genocide memorial, [[Kolkata]]]]\n\n[[File:Armenian Genocide 2.jpg|right|thumb|Armenian Genocide Remembrance Day, Kolkata]]\n[[File:Genocide 2011 1.JPG|thumb|Commemoration of the Armenian Genocide, Armenian Church in [[Volgograd]], [[Russia]]]]\n[[File:Isfahan Vank Church and Museum 03.jpg|right|thumb|Armenian Genocide Memorial, [[New Julfa]]]]\nBy the 1970s, [[Armenian Americans]], who had accumulated some wealth and political power, started efforts to lobby the U.S. government to recognize the genocide.<ref>{{cite web|author=Waal, Thomas de|url=https://www.foreignaffairs.com/articles/united-states/g-word|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150821213353/https://www.foreignaffairs.com/articles/united-states/g-word|url-status=dead|archive-date=2015-08-21|title=The G-Word|publisher=[[Foreign Affairs (magazine)|Foreign Affairs]]|date=January\u2013February 2015|accessdate=2019-06-06}}</ref>\n\nThe [[Armenian National Committee of America]] (ANCA) and the [[Armenian Assembly of America]] (AAA) [[Armenian American lobby|lobby]] for recognition in the [[United States Congress]], often in opposition to the [[Turkish lobby in the United States|Turkish lobby]].<ref name=\"Cameron, Fraser pp.91\" /><ref name=\"web.mit.edu\">{{cite web |url = http://web.mit.edu/cis/www/migration/pubs/rrwp/13_divided.pdf |title = Heather S. Gregg Divided They Conquer: The Success of Armenian Ethnic Lobbies in the United States }}</ref>\n\nDuring the later stages of the [[Cold War]], fringe militant movements among Armenians arose. One of the goals of these Armenian militants was to agitate world governments for Turkish and international recognition of the Armenian Genocide. Attacks on Turkish diplomats were committed in Europe, Asia and America. Two active groups which committed many of these attacks were the [[Armenian Secret Army for the Liberation of Armenia]] (ASALA) and the [[Armenian Revolutionary Army]] (ARA);<ref name=\"web.mit.edu\" /> both organizations stopped their military activities in the late 1980s.\n\nThe [[Armenians in India|Armenian community in Kolkata, India]], numbering approximately 150 people,<ref>{{cite news |title = Kolkata, Armenian celebrates Christms |url = http://www.thehindubusinessline.com/news/states/kolkata-armenians-celebrate-christmas/article5545315.ece |accessdate = February 4, 2014 |newspaper = Business Line |date = January 6, 2004 }}</ref> travel to the St John's Church in [[Hugli-Chuchura|Chinsurah]], annually, to observe Armenian Genocide Remembrance Day.<ref name=poulami>{{cite news |last = Banerjee |first = Poulami |title = Church Children |url = http://www.telegraphindia.com/1100523/jsp/calcutta/story_12477031.jsp |accessdate = February 5, 2014 |newspaper = The Telegraph. Calcutta |date = May 23, 2010 |location = Calcutta, India }}</ref> The community, along with visitors from countries such as Iran, Lebanon and Moscow held a memorial service at the 300-year-old [[Armenian Church of the Holy Nazareth|Armenian Holy Church of Nazareth]] in Kolkata to mark the 100th anniversary of the genocide.<ref>{{cite web |url = http://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/city/kolkata/Kolkatas-Armenians-mark-100th-year-of-genocide/articleshow/47045929.cms |title = Kolkata's Armenians mark 100th year of genocide |work = The Times of India |accessdate = June 2, 2016 }}</ref> Armenian students at the [[Jawaharlal Nehru University, Delhi|Jawaharlal Nehru University]] in [[New Delhi]] organised a candle lighting ceremony in the university campus and at the [[Sacred Heart Cathedral, New Delhi|Sacred Heart Cathedral]] in the city to mark the anniversary. A commemoration ceremony was also held at the [[Armenian Church, Chennai|Armenian Church]] in [[Chennai]].<ref>{{cite web |url = http://armedia.am/eng/news/17015/armenians-in-india-commemorated-the-armenian-genocide.html |title = Armenians in India Commemorated the Armenian Genocide |work = armedia.am |accessdate = June 2, 2016 }}</ref>\n\n== Developments since 2000 ==\nOn March 29, 2000 the [[Swedish parliament]] approved a report, recognizing the Armenian Genocide and calling for Turkey's greater openness and an \"unbiased independent and international research on the genocide committed against the Armenian people\".<ref>{{cite web |url = http://www.armenian-genocide.org/Affirmation.165/current_category.7/affirmation_detail.html |title = Sweden Parliament Report |publisher = Armenian-genocide.org |date = March 29, 2000 }}</ref> On June 12, 2008, the Swedish parliament voted by 245 to 37 (with 1 abstention, 66 absences) to reject a call for recognition of the 1915 genocide of the Ottoman Empire. On June 11 a long debate took place in the Swedish Parliament in regard to the Foreign Committee report on Human Rights, including five motions calling upon the Swedish Government and Parliament to officially recognize the genocide.<ref name=\"armtown\">{{cite news|url=http://www.armtown.com/news/en/pan/20080612/26307/ |title=PanArmenian.net \u2013 Swedish Parliament Refuses to Recognize Armenian Genocide |date=June 12, 2008 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110716082216/https://www.armtown.com/news/en/pan/20080612/26307/ |archivedate=July 16, 2011 |df=mdy }}</ref> The MPs adhered to the recommendation by the [[Ministry for Foreign Affairs (Sweden)|Swedish Foreign Ministry]] and Foreign Committee, arguing that there are \"disagreements among scholars\" in regard to the nature of the World War&nbsp;I events in Turkey, the non-retroactive nature of the UN Genocide Convention, and that the issue \"should be left to historians\". However, the Foreign Committee report stated that \"the Committee understands that what happened to Armenians, Assyrians/Syrians and Chaldeans during the Ottoman Empire's reign would probably be regarded as genocide according to the 1948&nbsp;convention, if it had been in power at the time of the event\".<ref>[https://data.riksdagen.se/fil/BFA75288-9F8A-46CB-8D6C-B2BBFD9DD2EA The Foreign Affairs Committee report 2007/08: UU9 - Human rights in Swedish Foreign policy]  Foreign Affairs Committee response to motions calling on the Swedish Parliament to recognize the Armenian Genocide {{in lang|sv}}</ref> Three days prior to the debate in the Parliament, a petition, signed by over 60 renowned genocide scholars was published, calling on politicians in general, and the Swedish parliamentarians in specific, not to abuse the name of science in denying a historic fact.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://itwasgenocide.armenica.org/ |title=Recognize the 1915 genocide for what it is |website=Itwasgenocide.armenica.org |date=  |author=60 named international scholars |accessdate= 4 June 2016}}</ref> On March 11, 2010, the Swedish parliament recognized the genocide.<ref>{{cite news|url= http://www.alertnet.org/thenews/newsdesk/LDE62A2IJ.htm |title=Sweden approves resolution on \"Armenian genocide\" |agency= Reuters|via=AlertNet |archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20100314070225/http://www.alertnet.org/thenews/newsdesk/LDE62A2IJ.htm |archive-date=2010-03-14|date=11 March 2010}}</ref>\n\nIn 2001, [[Abd al-Qadir Qaddura]], speaker of the Syrian Parliament, became the first high-ranking Syrian official to acknowledge the Armenian genocide when he wrote in the Book of Remembrance of the Armenian Genocide Monument and Museum in Yerevan: \"As we visit the Memorial and Museum of the Genocide that the Armenian nation suffered in 1915, we stand in full admiration and respect in front of those heroes that faced death with courage and heroism. Their children and grandchildren continued after them to immortalize their courage and struggle. \u2026 With great respect we bow our heads in memory of the martyrs of the Armenian nation \u2014 our friends \u2014 and hail their ability for resoluteness and triumph. We will work together to liberate every human being from aggression and oppression.\" In 2014 Syrian President [[Bashar al-Assad]] became the first Syrian head of state to acknowledge the mass murders of Armenians and identify the perpetrator as Ottoman Turkey, stating, \"The degree of savagery and inhumanity that the terrorists have reached reminds us of what happened in the Middle Ages in Europe over 500 years ago. In more recent modern times, it reminds us of the massacres perpetrated by the Ottomans against the Armenians, when they killed a million and a half Armenians and half a million Orthodox Syriacs in Syria and in Turkish territory.\" Although Assad did not use the world genocide, two days after Assad's statement [[Bashar Jaafari]], Syria's ambassador to the United Nations in Geneva, stated, \"How about the Armenian Genocide where 1.5 million people were killed?\"<ref name=\"armenianweekly.com\">{{cite web |last= Sassounian|first=Harut |url = http://www.armenianweekly.com/2014/01/29/sassounian-syrian-president-finally-recognizes-armenian-genocide/ |title = Sassounian: Syrian President Finally Recognizes Armenian Genocide |work = Armenian Weekly |date = 29 January 2014 |accessdate = 23 April 2015}}</ref>\n\nOn September 9, 2004, [[President of Iran|President]] [[Mohammad Khatami]] of Iran visited the Armenian Genocide Memorial at [[Tsitsernakaberd]] in Yerevan.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ourararat.com/eng/e_rec.htm|title=International Affirmation and Recognition of the Armenian Genocide|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20070715081139/http://www.ourararat.com/ENG/e_rec.htm |archive-date=15 July 2007 |website=OurArarat.com|date=April 2005}}</ref>\n\nOn June 15, 2005 the German [[Bundestag]] passed a resolution that \"honors and commemorates the victims of violence, murder and expulsion among the Armenian people before and during the First World War\". The [http://dipbt.bundestag.de/dip21/btd/15/056/1505689.pdf German resolution] also states:\n\n{{quote|The German parliament deplores the acts of the Government of the Ottoman Empire regarding the almost complete destruction of Armenians in Anatolia and also the inglorious role of the German Reich in the face of the organized expulsion and extermination of Armenians which it did not try to stop. Women, children and elderly were from February&nbsp;1915 sent on death marches towards the Syrian desert.}}\n\nThe expressions \"organized expulsion and extermination\" resulting in the \"almost complete destruction of Armenians\" is sufficient in any language to amount to formal recognition of the Armenian Genocide, although of course the crime of 'genocide' had not been legally defined in 1915. The Resolution also contains an apology for German responsibility as a then ally of Turkey.<ref name=\"bundestag\">{{cite web|url=http://www.armenian-genocide.org/Affirmation.339/current_category.7/affirmation_detail.html|title=Germany Parliament Resolution|publisher=[[Armenian National Institute]]|date=15 June 2005|accessdate=2019-03-19}}</ref><ref name=\"Deutshe Welle\">{{cite web|url= https://www.dw.com/en/germany-to-turkey-own-up-to-massacre/a-1560270|title=Germany to Turkey: Own Up to Massacre|publisher=Deutsche Welle|date=22 April 2005|accessdate=2019-03-19}}</ref>\n\nOn September 4, 2006, [[Member of the European Parliament|Members of the European Parliament]] voted for the inclusion of a clause prompting Turkey \"to recognize the Armenian genocide as a condition for its EU&nbsp;accession\" in a highly critical report, which was adopted by a broad majority in the foreign relations committee of the [[European Parliament]].<ref>{{cite web|last=Kubosova|first=Lucia |url=http://euobserver.com/9/22331/?rk=1 |title=MEPs back Armenia genocide clause in Turkey report|work=[[EU Observer]]|date=5 September 2006|accessdate=2019-03-19}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.euractiv.com/en/enlargement/parliament-faces-crucial-enlargement-decisions/article-158105 |title=Parliament faces crucial enlargement decisions |work=EurActiv |date=25 September 2006|url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20071013142326/http://euractiv.com/en/enlargement/parliament-faces-crucial-enlargement-decisions/article-158105 |archivedate=13 October 2007}}</ref> This requirement was later dropped on September 27, 2006 by the general assembly of the European Parliament by 429 votes in favor to 71 against, with 125 abstentions.<ref>{{cite press release |url = http://www.europarl.europa.eu/sides/getDoc.do?language=EN&type=IM-PRESS&reference=20060922IPR10896 |title = European Parliament critical of slowdown in Turkey's reform process |date = September 27, 2006 |publisher = [[European Parliament]] }}</ref>\nIn dropping the pre-condition of acceptance of the Armenian Genocide, (which could not be legally demanded of Turkey), The European Parliament said: \"MEPs nevertheless stress that, although the recognition of the Armenian genocide as such is formally not one of the Copenhagen criteria, it is indispensable for a country on the road to membership to come to terms with and recognize its past.\"\n\nOn September 26, 2006, the two largest political parties in the Netherlands, [[Christian Democratic Appeal]] (CDA) and the [[Labour Party (Netherlands)|Labour Party]] (PvdA), removed three Turkish-Dutch candidates for the [[Dutch general election, 2006|2006 general election]], because they either denied or refused to publicly declare that the Armenian Genocide had happened. The magazine ''[[HP/De Tijd]]'' reported that the number 2 of the PvdA list of candidates, [[Nebahat Albayrak]] (who was born in Turkey and is of Turkish descent) had acknowledged that the term \"genocide\" was appropriate to describe the events. Albayrak denied having said this and accused the press of putting words in her mouth, saying that \"I'm not a politician that will trample my identity. I've always defended the same views everywhere with regard to the 'genocide'\".<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.turkishdailynews.com.tr/article.php?enewsid=56157|title=I did not say proved genocide took place| archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20070930181315/http://www.turkishdailynews.com.tr/article.php?enewsid=56157 |archive-date=30 September 2007|work=[[Turkish Daily News]]|date=9 October 2006}}</ref> It was reported that a large section of the Turkish minority were considering boycotting the elections.<ref>{{cite news |title = Turkish to boycott election over Armenian 'genocide' |url = http://www.expatica.com/actual/article.asp?subchannel_id=1&story_id=33549 |work = Expatica News |date = October 5, 2006 }}</ref> [[Turks in the Netherlands|Netherlands' Turkish minority]] numbers 365,000 people, out of which 235,000 are eligible to vote.\n\nOn November 29, 2006, the lower house of Argentina's parliament adopted a resolution recognizing the Armenian Genocide. The bill was overwhelmingly adopted by the assembly and declared April 24, the international day of remembrance for the Armenian genocide as an official \"day of mutual tolerance and respect\" among peoples around the world.\n\nOn April 20, 2007, the [[Basque Parliament]] approved an institutional declaration recognising the Armenian Genocide. The Basque Parliament included six articles where it affirms the authenticity of the Armenian Genocide and declares sympathy to the Armenians, while at the same time denouncing Turkey's negation of the genocide and its economic blockade imposed on Armenia.<ref>{{cite web |title = En el 90.\u00ba aniversario del genocidio armenio |date = April 27, 2007 |publisher = [[Basque Parliament]] |url = http://www.parlamento.euskadi.net/BASIS/izaro/webx/cm_bopvc/DDW?W=boc_clave='08110500003320070427016312'&R=N |accessdate = May 12, 2007 |language = es |archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20160121023409/http://www.parlamento.euskadi.net/BASIS/izaro/webx/cm_bopvc/DDW?W=boc_clave='08110500003320070427016312'&R=N |archive-date = January 21, 2016 |url-status = dead |df = mdy-all }}</ref>\n\n[[File:Dmitry Medvedev at Armenian Genocide memorial-2.jpg|thumb|Russian President [[Dmitry Medvedev]] laying a wreath at the Armenian Genocide Memorial, October 2008]]\n\nOn June 5, 2007, the [[Chilean Senate]] unanimously adopted a legislation recognising the Armenian Genocide and urging its government to support a key 1985 United Nations Subcommission report properly describing this crime against humanity as a clear instance of genocide.<ref>{{cite web |url = http://www.anca.org/press_releases/press_releases.php?prid=1205 |title = Chilean Senate Unanimously Recognizes Armenian Genocide |publisher = Anca.org }}</ref>\n\nOn November 23, 2007, the [[Mercosur]] parliament adopted a resolution recognising the \"Armenian Genocide, perpetrated by the Ottoman Empire, which took 1.5&nbsp;million lives from 1915 to 1923\". The Mercosur resolution also expressed its support for the Armenian Cause and called on all countries to recognize the genocide.<ref>{{cite web |url = http://www.mercopress.com/vernoticia.do?id=11955&formato=pdf |title = Mercosur recognises the Armenian Genocide |publisher = Mercopress.com |date = November 23, 2007 }}</ref>\n\nOn March 5, 2010, the [[Catalonia|Catalan]] Parliament recognized the Armenian Genocide on the initiative of the members of [[Barcelona]]'s Friendship Union with Armenia.<ref name=\"Catalonia\" />\n\nOn March 11, 2010 the Swedish Parliament voted to describe the massacre of Armenians by the Ottoman Empire in 1915 as genocide. The resolution was adopted with 131 deputies voting in favour of the resolution and 130 voting against it.\n\nOn March 25, 2010 the [[Serbian Radical Party]] submitted a draft resolution to the Serbian parliament condemning the genocide committed by Ottoman Turkey against Armenians from 1915 to 1923. SRS submitted the draft so that Serbia can join the countries which have condemned the genocide.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.b92.net/eng/news/politics-article.php?yyyy=2010&mm=03&dd=25&nav_id=66050 |title=Info \u2013 SRS submits \"draft Armenian genocide resolution\" |publisher=B92 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100327080231/http://www.b92.net/eng/news/politics-article.php?yyyy=2010&mm=03&dd=25&nav_id=66050 |archivedate=March 27, 2010 }}</ref> As of March 10, 2014, Serbia does not recognize the events as a genocide,<ref>{{cite news |url = http://armenpress.am/eng/news/753209/serbian-fm-commemorates-armenian-genocide-victims.html |title = Serbian FM commemorates Armenian Genocide victims |agency = Armenpress |date = 10 March 2014 |accessdate = 23 April 2015}}</ref> thus it can be said the draft has failed.\n\nOn February 17, 2011, Chinese foreign minister [[Yang Jiechi]] paid tribute to the memory of the Armenian Genocide victims during his visit to Armenia. He also met with the head of Armenia's national church, Catholicos of All Armenians [[Karekin II]], and discussed the recognition of the Armenian Genocide.<ref>{{cite web |url = http://www.tamilguardian.com/article.asp?articleid=3010 |title = China and the Armenian genocide |work = Tamil Guardian|date = 16 February 2011|accessdate = 2 June 2016}}</ref>\n\nDespite the fact that the Czech Republic has not formally recognized the Armenian Genocide, during his meeting with Armenia's President [[Serzh Sargsyan]] in January 2014, the Czech President [[Milo\u0161 Zeman]] stated: \"Next year marks the 100th anniversary of the Armenian Genocide. In 1915 1.5 million Armenians were killed.\"<ref>{{cite news |title = Czech President Recognizes Genocide |url = http://asbarez.com/119047/czech-president-recognizes-genocide/ |accessdate = February 1, 2014 |newspaper = [[Asbarez]] |date = January 31, 2014 }}</ref>\n\nOn June 20, 2014, the [[Presbyterian Church (USA)]] adopted a resolution recognizing the Armenian Genocide and adopting the 2015 church calendar designating April 26 as the day for its observance.<ref name=\"theorthodoxchurch.info\" /><ref name=\"mirrorspectator.com\" /> It also directed the church's Mission Agency to prepare educational and liturgical resources for member churches in preparation for this event.<ref name=\"mirrorspectator.com\" /> This resolution was the first of its kind for a major American church body.<ref name=\"mirrorspectator.com\" />\n\nOn June 23, 2014 the parliament of [[Spain]]'s autonomous community of [[Navarre]] adopted a measure recognizing the Armenian Genocide. The measure came after a series of visits by members of the Navarre parliament to Armenia and Artsakh.<ref>{{cite news |title = Basque Country, Artsakh Consider Establishing Relations |url = http://asbarez.com/124561/basque-country-artsakh-consider-establishing-relations/ |work = Asbarez |date = 30 June 2014|accessdate=2019-03-19}}</ref>\n\nOn November 26, 2014, the Plurinational Legislative Assembly of [[Bolivia]] unanimously passed a resolution in solidarity with the claims of the Armenian people and condemning \"all denialist policy regarding the genocide and crimes against humanity suffered by the Armenian nation.\"<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.prensaarmenia.com.ar/2014/11/bolivia-unanimously-approved-resolution.html|title=Bolivia Unanimously Approved a Resolution on the Armenian Genocide |publisher=Prensaarmenia.com}}</ref>\n\nOn March 11, 2015, American actor [[George Clooney]] showed solidarity and support in a day of remembrance marking the 100th anniversary of the Armenian Genocide at an event in New York City. Clooney took to the stage and spoke about the significance of the centennial and of recognizing the genocide. Clooney was joined by his wife [[Amal Clooney]], who went before Europe's top human rights court in January, representing Armenia, to argue against a man convicted of denying the 1915 Armenian Genocide.{{cn|date=April 2020}}\n\nOn March 17, 2015, the [[People's Council of Syria]]\u2014during a session dedicated to the 100th anniversary of the genocide\u2014condemned the [[Ottoman Empire]] for its responsibility for the Armenian Genocide. The speaker of the parliament [[Mohammad Jihad al-Laham]] issued a statement on behalf of the members, where he expressed solidarity with the Armenians worldwide in their struggle for justice.<ref>{{cite web |url = http://arabi-press.com/news/866143 |script-title=ar:\u0645\u062c\u0644\u0633 \u0627\u0644\u0634\u0639\u0628 \u0627\u0644\u0633\u0648\u0631\u064a: \u0645\u062a\u0636\u0627\u0645\u0646\u0648\u0646 \u0645\u0639 \u0627\u0644\u0634\u0639\u0628 \u0627\u0644\u0623\u0631\u0645\u0646\u064a \u0641\u064a \u0630\u0643\u0631 \u0627\u0644\u0645\u062c\u0632\u0631\u0629 \u0627\u0644\u0639\u062b\u0645\u0627\u0646\u064a\u0629 |date=17 March 2015 |website= arabi-press.com |language=ar|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160306102410/http://arabi-press.com/news/866143|archive-date=2016-03-06}}</ref>\n\nOn March 27, 2015, Armenian and Greek youth held a protest in the Greek capital of [[Athens]]. Protesters demanded that [[European Union]] member states end denial policies, recognize the Armenian Genocide, and subject deniers to criminal liability. The protesters further called on the European Union to pressure Turkey to recognize the genocide and take action to compensate for the material and non-material losses and restoration of the historic rights of the Armenian nation.<ref>{{cite news |url = http://armenpress.am/eng/news/799503/greek-armenian-youth-submit-requisition-to-eu-representative-for-armenian-genocide-recognition.html |title = Greek-Armenian youth submit requisition to EU representative for Armenian Genocide recognition |date = 27 March 2015 |agency = Armenpress|accessdate=2019-03-19}}</ref>\n\nOn April 2, 2015, the popular American band [[System of a Down]] embarked on their [[Wake Up The Souls Tour]], which kicked off April 6 and culminates with the band's first performance in Armenia's capital city of Yerevan on April 23. \"The goal is to raise awareness about the Armenian Genocide, and also to put the idea into people's minds that justice can prevail, even if it's been a hundred years,\" said band member [[Serj Tankian]]. The group will visit a total of 14 cities across the world.<ref>{{cite web |last = Duelund |first = Theis |url = http://www.laweekly.com/music/system-of-a-down-push-for-recognition-of-the-armenian-genocide-5463496 |title = System of a Down Push for Recognition of the Armenian Genocide |work = LA Weekly |date = 2 April 2015 |accessdate = 23 April 2015}}</ref>\n\nOn April 4, 2015, forty-nine members of the [[United States House of Representatives]] have written a letter to U.S. President [[Barack Obama]] urging him to recognize the mass killings of the Armenians at the hands of the Ottomans in 1915 as genocide, claiming that the move will help improve [[Armenia\u2013Turkey relations]]. The lawmakers said a clear recognition of the 1915 events as genocide, as Armenians mark its centennial this year, would affirm that it is not an allegation but a \"widely documented fact supported by an overwhelming body of historical evidence.\" <ref>{{cite web |url = http://www.todayszaman.com/diplomacy_49-us-lawmakers-urge-obama-to-recognize-armenian-genocide-in-letter_377142.html |title = 49 US lawmakers urge Obama to recognize Armenian 'genocide' in letter |date = April 4, 2015 |work = TodaysZaman }}</ref>\n\nOn April 6, 2015, Armenian-American reality stars [[Kim Kardashian]] and [[Khlo\u00e9 Kardashian]] traveled to Armenia. During their stay, the sisters visited the [[Tsitsernakaberd]] Genocide Memorial in Yerevan and in-doing so, brought global media attention to the recognition of the Armenian Genocide. Kim Kardashian's husband [[Kanye West]] also visited the Republic.<ref>{{cite news |last=Harris|first= Rachel Lee|url = https://www.nytimes.com/2015/04/14/travel/the-kardashians-show-support-for-armenia.html |title= The Kardashians Show Support for Armenia|date= 14 April 2015 |work=The New York Times|accessdate= 24 April 2016}}</ref>\n\nOn April 7, 2015, the [[Ng\u0101puhi]] leader David Rankin has called for [[M\u0101ori people]] to boycott this year's centennial ANZAC commemorations because the Turkish Government is using the event to deflect attention from the Armenian Genocide. Mr Rankin stated that \"the Armenian population was slaughtered by the colonizing Turks and our involvement in the ANZAC centennial at Gallipoli is supporting the genocide of the colonizer. Mr Rankin is calling on the Maori of [[New Zealand]] and other indigenous groups to boycott this year's ANZAC Day events and as a sign of their solidarity with the Armenians, to stop wearing poppies this year.<ref>{{cite press release|first=Rankin|last=David |title = Iwi leader calls for Maori Boycott of ANZAC Day |url = http://www.scoop.co.nz/stories/PO1504/S00052/iwi-leader-calls-for-maori-boycott-of-anzac-day.htm |website= Scoop |date = 7 April 2015|accessdate=2019-03-19}}</ref> The [[Green Party of Aotearoa New Zealand]] also supports the move to recognize the Armenian Genocide. The Green Party human rights spokesperson [[Catherine Delahunty]] stated that New Zealand should be using its spot on the [[United Nations Security Council]] to advocate for genocide recognition.<ref>{{cite web |url = http://www.newstalkzb.co.nz/news/national/green-party-calls-for-nz-recognition-of-armenian-genocide/ |title = Green Party calls for NZ recognition of Armenian Genocide |author = Kay Gregory |work = newstalkzb.co.nz |accessdate = June 2, 2016 }}</ref>\n\nOn April 12, 2015, [[Pope Francis]] described the massacres of 1.5 million Armenians in Ottoman Turkey as \"the first genocide of the 20th century\" during an unprecedented Vatican Mass dedicated to the 100th anniversary of the tragedy. Francis remembered the victims of \"that immense and senseless slaughter\" at the start of the Mass at [[St. Peter's Basilica]], which was attended by President Serzh Sarkisian, the supreme heads of the Armenian Apostolic Churches and hundreds of Armenian Catholics.<ref>{{cite news |last1 = Danielyan |first1 = Emil |title = Pope Reaffirms Armenian Genocide Recognition |url = http://www.azatutyun.am/content/article/26951607.html |agency = Azatutyun |date = April 12, 2015 }}</ref> Turkey responded by recalling its ambassador to the [[Holy See]].<ref>{{cite web |last= Onyanga-Omara|first=Jane|url = https://www.usatoday.com/story/news/world/2015/04/12/pope-armenia/25667197/ |title = Turkey angry at pope after 'genocide' remarks |work = USA Today |date = 12 April 2015 |accessdate = 12 April 2015}}</ref>\n\nOn April 14, 2015, the Parliament of [[Corsica]] adopted a resolution recognizing the fact of the Armenian Genocide. With this resolution, the [[Corsican Assembly]] urged Turkey to recognize the Genocide and normalize relations with Armenia. The resolution was introduced by the Femu a Corsica political coalition.<ref>{{cite web |url = http://artsakhpress.am/eng/news/16512/corsican-assembly-demands-armenian-genocide-recognition-from-turkey.html |title = Corsican Assembly demands Armenian Genocide recognition from Turkey |work = artsakhpress.am |accessdate = June 2, 2016 }}</ref>\n\nOn April 15, 2015, the [[European Parliament]] adopted a resolution by a majority vote that calls the massacre a century ago of up to 1.5 million Armenians by Ottoman Turkish forces a genocide. The motion, which garnered support from all political groups, encouraged Turkey to \"use the commemoration of the centenary of the Armenian Genocide as an important opportunity\" to open its archives, \"come to terms with its past\" as well as recognize the genocide. By doing so, Turkey would pave the way for a \"genuine reconciliation between the Turkish and Armenian peoples\". The document calls on Turkey to restore its diplomatic ties with Armenia, open the border and strive for economic integration.<ref>{{cite news |title = EU Parliament adopts resolution calling on Turkey to recognize Armenian genocide |url = http://rt.com/news/250029-eu-parliament-turkey-genocide/ |agency = Russia Today |date = April 15, 2015 }}</ref> The European Parliament further called on all [[European Union]] member states to recognize the Armenian Genocide.<ref>{{cite news |title = [UPDATED] European Parliament Adopts Bill Urging Turkey to Recognize Genocide |url = http://asbarez.com/134064/european-parliament-adopts-bill-urging-turkey-to-recognize-genocide/ |work= Asbarez |date = 15 April 2015|accessdate=2019-03-19}}</ref>\n\nOn April 17, 2015, Armenian religious and secular organizations in [[Georgia (country)|Georgia]] have petitioned the country's parliament to begin formal debates on the recognition of the Armenian Genocide.<ref>{{cite web |author = |url = http://news.am/eng/news/262446.html |title = Georgia Armenians demand country's parliament to discuss Genocide issue |publisher = News.am |date = April 17, 2015 |accessdate = April 23, 2015 }}</ref> On April 24, 2015, thousands marched in the province of [[Javakheti]] demanding that Turkey recognize the genocide. Another rally took place near the Turkish embassy in [[Tbilisi]].<ref>{{cite web |url = http://hetq.am/eng/news/59837/armenians-of-javakhk-march-demand-genocide-recognition-from-turkey.html |title = Armenians of Javakhk March: Demand Genocide Recognition from Turkey |date = April 23, 2015 |work = hetq.am }}</ref>\n\nOn April 18, 2015, the [[Austrian People's Party]] and the [[Social Democratic Party of Austria]] presented a resolution that condemns the Armenian Genocide to the Parliament of [[Austria]].<ref>{{cite web |author = |url = http://news.am/eng/news/262685.html |title = Austria parliament to condemn Armenian Genocide? |publisher = News.am |date = April 18, 2015 |accessdate = April 23, 2015 }}</ref> On April 21, 2015 the Austrian parliament officially adopted a statement condemning the Armenian Genocide and called on Turkey to face its past. All six factions of the Austrian parliament signed up to the statement that also emphasizes the responsibility of [[Austria-Hungary]], as an ally of the Ottoman Empire during World War I, in the Armenian Genocide.<ref>{{cite web |url = http://www.panarmenian.net/eng/news/190959/ |title = Austrian parliament adopts statement condemning Armenian Genocide |publisher = Panarmenian.Net |date =  |accessdate = April 23, 2015 }}</ref>\n\nOn April 20, 2015, German Chancellor [[Angela Merkel]]'s spokesman [[Steffen Seibert]] said the government of [[Germany]] would support a resolution in parliament on Friday declaring the Armenian Genocide an example of genocide. Chancellor Angela Merkel and her coalition, including the [[Christian Democratic Union of Germany]] will vote on April 24 to label the murders as genocide as defined by the United Nations in 1948. The lower house vote is on the same day as leaders meet in the Armenian capital of [[Yerevan]] to commemorate the massacre that began in April 1915. Germany has been under pressure from some of its European partners to follow their example and more fully recognize the depth of the Armenian tragedy.<ref>{{cite news |last1 = Nicola |first1 = Stefan |last2=Parkin|first2= Brian|title = Germany Plans to Recognize Armenian Massacre in 1915 as Genocide |url = https://www.bloomberg.com/news/articles/2015-04-20/germany-plans-to-recognize-armenian-massacre-in-1915-as-genocide |agency = Bloomberg |date = 20 April 2015|accessdate=2019-03-19}}</ref>\n\nOn April 21, 2015, members of the Serbian opposition political group [[New Party (Serbia)|New Party]], submitted a draft resolution on the recognition and condemnation of genocide perpetrated by the Ottoman Empire to the Parliament of [[Serbia]]. New Party is calling on the Serbian government and citizens to observe April 24 as a day of remembrance of the victims of the Armenian Genocide. The draft resolution also calls on other countries, including Turkey, and international organizations to recognize and condemn the genocide against the Armenian people in the hopes to prevent such crimes from happening in the future.<ref>{{cite web |url = http://www.yerkirmedia.am/?act=news&lan=en&id=26064 |title = Draft resolution on Armenian Genocide recognition and condemnation introduced in Serbian parliament|publisher= Yerkir Media |date=21 April 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160416024448/http://yerkirmedia.am/?act=news&lan=en&id=26064|archive-date=2016-04-16}}</ref>\n\nOn April 22, 2015, Israeli President [[Reuven Rivlin]] spoke out strongly on the question of the Armenian Genocide in a closed session with journalists in [[Jerusalem]]. Rivlin drew a direct historical link between the world's failure to prevent the Armenian Genocide and the Holocaust. \"The Nazis,\" he said, \"used the Armenian Genocide as something that gave them permission to bring the Holocaust into reality.\" <ref>{{cite web |url = http://www.thetower.org/1920-breaking-israels-president-endorses-popes-comments-on-armenian-genocide/ |title = Breaking: Israel's President Endorses Pope's Comments on Armenian Genocide \u2013 The Tower |work = The Tower |date=22 April 2015 |accessdate = 2 June 2016}}</ref>\n\nOn April 22, 2015, the President of Armenia, Serzh Sargsyan expressed his gratitude to the People's Council of Syria for its steps aimed at the recognition of the Armenian Genocide. The speaker of the People's Council of the [[Syrian Arab Republic]], Mohammad Jihad al-Laham, stated that Syria recognizes the Armenian Genocide committed by the Ottoman Empire.<ref>{{cite web |last=Ghazanchyan|first=Siranush \n|url = http://www.armradio.am/en/2015/04/22/syria-recognizes-the-armenian-genocide-committed-by-the-ottoman-empire-parliament-speaker-says/ |title = Syria recognizes the Armenian Genocide committed by the Ottoman Empire, Parliament Speaker says |publisher= Public Radio of Armenia|date=22 April 2015|accessdate = 2 June 2016}}</ref>\n\nOn April 23, 2015, Russian President [[Vladimir Putin]] described the 1915 Armenian massacres in Ottoman Turkey as genocide ahead of his participation in upcoming official ceremonies in Yerevan to mark the 100th anniversary of the tragedy. \"One century on, we bow our heads in memory of all victims of this tragedy which our country has always perceived as its own pain and calamity,\" he said.<ref>{{cite web |url = http://asbarez.com/134362/putin-reaffirms-russian-recognition-of-armenian-genocide/ |title = Putin Reaffirms Russian Recognition of Armenian Genocide |work = Asbarez |date=23 April 2015|accessdate = 2 June 2016}}</ref>\n\nOn April 23, 2015, the [[Flemish Parliament]] of [[Belgium]] unanimously adopted a resolution to fully recognize the Armenian Genocide. The motion was put forward by all political parties of [[Flanders]] including the [[Christen-Democratisch en Vlaams]] party. The motion further called on Turkey to recognize the massacres as a genocide.<ref>{{cite news|url = http://armenpress.am/eng/news/803046/flemish-parliament-adopts-resolution-recognizing-armenian-genocide.html |title = Flemish Parliament adopts resolution recognizing Armenian Genocide |date = 23 April 2015 |agency = Armenpress |accessdate=2019-03-19}}</ref>\n\nOn April 24, 2015, the President of Serbia, [[Tomislav Nikoli\u0107]], stated that the people of [[Serbia]] realize what happened to the Armenians in the Ottoman Empire and that a monstrous genocide did occur. The President, along with other world leaders, travelled to the Armenian capital of Yerevan to commemorate the centennial of the genocide. The denial of historical truth adversely affects the level of awareness,\" the Serbian president stressed, and added: \"We have not come here to be against or for someone, but to honor the memory of the victims of the people of Armenia.\" <ref>{{cite web |url = http://news.am/eng/news/263718.html |title = Serbia President: Do we have the right not to honor Armenian Genocide victims? (PHOTOS) |work = news.am |accessdate = June 2, 2016 }}</ref>\n\nOn April 24, 2015 in [[Los Angeles]], more than 130,000 people took part in the [[2015 Armenian March for Justice|March for Justice]] to mark the centennial of the Armenian Genocide. Demonstrators started the march from the Little Armenia neighborhood and proceeded to walk {{convert|6|mi|km|order=flip|abbr=on|0}} to the Turkish consulate. Demonstrators demanded that the killing of around 1.5 million Armenians by Ottoman Turks in 1915 be recognized as a genocide.<ref>{{cite web |url = http://rt.com/usa/252945-los-angeles-armenian-genocide-march/ |title = Armenian genocide: 130K march in LA to mark 100th anniversary (PHOTO, VIDEO) |work = RT.com |date=25 April 2015|accessdate = 2 June 2016}}</ref>\n\nOn April 24, 2015, the lights of the [[Eiffel Tower]] in [[Paris]] and the [[Coliseum]] in [[Rome]] went dark in recognition and remembrance of the Armenian Genocide. Several media outlets reported that Europe stood with Armenia at this time.<ref>{{cite web |url = https://horizonweekly.ca/en/66422-2/ |title = Eiffel Tower and Coliseum go dark to mark Armenian Genocide |work = Horizon Weekly |date=25 April 2015|accessdate = 2 June 2016}}</ref>\n\nOn April 25, 2015, the entire political elite of [[Uruguay]] participated in commemorating the centennial of the Armenian Genocide in [[Montevideo]]. Among the participants were President [[Tabar\u00e9 V\u00e1zquez]] and Vice-President [[Ra\u00fal Fernando Sendic Rodr\u00edguez]]. The high-ranking guests talked about the need for international recognition of the Armenian Genocide and criticized Turkey's denial. Uruguay was the first country to recognize the Armenian Genocide in 1965.<ref>{{cite news|url = http://armenpress.am/eng/news/803289/president-of-uruguay-tabar%C3%A9-v%C3%A1zquez-participated-in-armenian-genocide-centennial-event.html |title = President of Uruguay Tabar\u00e9 V\u00e1zquez participated in Armenian Genocide Centennial event |date = 25 April 2015 |agency = Armenpress|accessdate=2019-03-19}}</ref>\n\nThroughout April 2015, several American states have adopted resolutions on the occasion of the Armenian Genocide centennial. [[Wisconsin]] commemorated the \"Day of Remembrance for the 100th Anniversary of the Armenian Genocide of 1915 to 1923 with a joint resolution. [[Pennsylvania]] unanimously passed H.R. 265 designating April 24, 2015, as \"Pennsylvania's Day of Remembrance of the 100th anniversary of the Armenian Genocide. [[Tennessee]] passed HR 100 designating April 24 as the official day of remembrance for the Armenian Genocide. The [[New York State Assembly]] passed Res.374 \"intended to counter the tide of revisionist history which purports that the Armenian Genocide never took place.\" The [[Georgia House of Representatives]] passed Resolution H.R. 904 which declares April 24 as Armenian Genocide Remembrance Day.<ref>{{cite news|url = http://armenpress.am/eng/news/800248/state-of-georgia-has-declared-april-24th-as-armenian-genocide-remembrance-day.html |title = State of Georgia has declared April 24th as Armenian Genocide Remembrance Day |date = 2 April 2015 |agency= Armenpress| accessdate=2019-03-19}}</ref> As of April 2015, 44 out of 50 U.S. states have, by legislation or proclamation, recognized the Armenian Genocide.<ref>{{cite web |url = http://news.am/eng/news/263957.html |title = Several American states pass resolutions on Armenian Genocide Centennial |work = news.am |accessdate = June 2, 2016 }}</ref>\n\nOn April 27, 2015, a call to recognize the killing of an estimated 1.5 million Armenians as \"genocide\", was supported by the leaders of the main Irish churches. Clergy from seven Christian denominations and a representative of the Jewish Community were among those calling on [[Republic of Ireland]] to recognize the genocide. Roman Catholic auxiliary bishop of Dublin [[Raymond Field (bishop)|Raymond Field]] said to the Armenians \"I stand in solidarity with you, and we share your pain and sadness.\" [[Church of Ireland]] [[Archbishop of Dublin (Church of Ireland)|Archbishop of Dublin]] Dr [[Michael Jackson (bishop)|Michael Jackson]] also described the killing as a \"genocide\" which demanded \"recognition and response\".<ref>{{cite web |last=Ghazanchyan|first=Siranush |url = http://www.armradio.am/en/2015/04/27/irish-religious-leaders-support-call-to-recognise-armenian-genocide/ |title = Irish religious leaders support call to recognise Armenian Genocide |publisher= Public Radio of Armenia |date=27 April 2015|accessdate = 2 June 2016}}</ref> On the same day, Armenia called on Ireland to recognize the genocide, the call was made by the Armenian Consul to Ireland.<ref>{{cite web |last=Ghazanchyan|first=Siranush |url = http://www.armradio.am/en/2015/04/27/calls-for-ireland-to-recognise-armenian-genocide/ |title = Calls for Ireland to recognise Armenian Genocide |publisher= Public Radio of Armenia |date=27 April 2015|accessdate = 2 June 2016}}</ref>\n\nOn April 29, 2015, members of the [[Kurdistan Parliament]] in [[Iraq]] submitted a legislative proposal to recognize the events of 1915 as the Armenian Genocide. The [[Patriotic Union of Kurdistan]] extended its support of the proposal. The draft law also proposes to declare April 24 as an official non-working day in [[Iraqi Kurdistan]].<ref>{{cite news|url = http://armenpress.am/eng/news/803796/parliament-of-iraqi-kurdistan-to-discuss-proposal-for-armenian-genocide-recognition.html |title = Parliament of Iraqi Kurdistan to discuss proposal for Armenian Genocide recognition |date = 29 April 2015 |agency = Armenpress|accessdate=2019-03-19}}</ref>\n\nOn May 6, 2015, the Chamber of Deputies of the Grand Duchy of [[Luxembourg]] adopted unanimously a resolution recognizing and condemning the Armenian Genocide.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://asbarez.com/135807/luxembourg-recognizes-armenian-genocide |title=Luxembourg Recognizes Armenian Genocide |work=Asbarez|date=6 May 2015|accessdate=2019-03-19}}</ref>\n\nOn May 30, 2015, the [[Young European Socialists]] gathered in Riga, [[Latvia]] where a resolution recognizing the Armenian Genocide was passed. The group also condemned Turkey's denial of the crime and called on Turkey to begin a process of reparations for the genocide.<ref>{{cite web |url = http://asbarez.com/136472/young-european-socialists-bureau-adopts-resolution-on-armenian-genocide/ |title = Young European Socialists Bureau Adopts Resolution on Armenian Genocide |work = Asbarez |date=2 June 2015|accessdate = 24 April 2016}}</ref>\n\nOn June 2, 2015, the Federal Senate of [[Brazil]] passed a resolution recognizing the Armenian Genocide. The resolution expresses its \"solidarity with the Armenian people during the course of the centenary of the campaign of extermination of its population\" and states that \"the Senate recognizes the Armenian Genocide, whose centenary was commemorated on April 24, 2015.\"<ref>{{cite news|url=http://armenianweekly.com/2015/06/03/federal-senate-of-brazil-recognizes-armenian-genocide |title=Federal Senate of Brazil Recognizes Armenian Genocide|work=Armenian Weekly|date=June 3, 2015}}</ref>\n\nOn October 29, 2015, the Senate of the Republic of [[Paraguay]] unanimously approved an official recognition of the Armenian Genocide. \"The Senate of the Republic of Paraguay recognizes the genocide of the Armenian people in the period 1915-1923, committed by the Turkish-Ottoman Empire, when commemorating this year the centenary of that crime against humanity,\" reads Article 1 of the statement presented by the Progressive Democratic Party.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://asbarez.com/141178/paraguays-senate-recognizes-armenian-genocide |title=Paraguay's Senate Recognizes Armenian Genocide |work=Asbarez|date=29 October 2015|accessdate=2019-03-19}}</ref>\n\nOn November 30, 2015, the [[Parliament of South Ossetia]] will consider the issue of recognition of the Armenian Genocide, as announced by Speaker [[Anatoly Bibilov]]. \"We regret that South Ossetia has not recognized the Armenian Genocide until now. The issue is on the parliament agenda now, and will be put on a discussion. It's necessary to give a proper assessment to the crime committed in the Ottoman Empire and condemn the policy of denial of genocide,\" he said. He added that South Ossetia is not afraid of damaging ties with Turkey, as there are no relations as such.<ref>{{cite web |last=Ghazanchyan|first=Siranush|url = http://www.armradio.am/en/2015/11/30/south-ossetia-considers-recognition-of-armenian-genocide/ |title = South Ossetia considers recognition of Armenian Genocide |publisher= Public Radio of Armenia |date=30 November 2015|accessdate = 24 April 2016}}</ref>\n\nOn December 2, 2015, the Parliament of [[Aragon]] in [[Spain]], adopted a declaration recognizing and condemning the Armenian Genocide.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://armeniangenocide100.org/en/spains-aragon-recognizes-armenian-genocide|title=Spain's Aragon recognizes Armenian Genocide|publisher=Armeniangenocide100.org|access-date=September 20, 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160927082700/http://armeniangenocide100.org/en/spains-aragon-recognizes-armenian-genocide/|archive-date=September 27, 2016|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\nOn June 2, 2016, [[Germany]]'s [[Bundestag]] passed a resolution recognizing the Armenian Genocide and admitting its part of responsibility for it, as the main ally of the Ottoman Empire during World War I, which led to a furious reaction in Turkey.<ref>{{cite news |url = https://www.bbc.com/news/world-europe-36433114 |title = German MPs recognise Armenian 'genocide' amid Turkish fury|work =BBC News|date = 2 June 2016 |accessdate = 2 June 2016}}</ref> Turkish President [[Recep Tayyip Erdo\u011fan]] has said German lawmakers of Turkish origin who voted for the resolution have \"tainted blood\" and that their blood \"must be tested in a lab.\" The president of Germany's parliament, [[Norbert Lammert]] said he was shocked that threats against the parliamentarians had been backed by high-ranking politicians, and said parliament would respond with all legal options. Also, [[Martin Schulz]], a member of the [[Social Democratic Party of Germany]] (SPD) and president of the European Parliament condemned Erdo\u011fan's comments.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.hurriyetdailynews.com/german-parliament-condemns-turkish-threats-against-lawmakers.aspx?pageID=238&nID=100288&NewsCatID=351|title=German parliament condemns Turkish 'threats' against lawmakers|work=H\u00fcrriyet Daily News|date=9 June 2016|accessdate=2019-03-19}}</ref> German foreign ministry had warned lawmakers with Turkish origin against travel to Turkey because their safety could not be guaranteed and also they received increased police protection and further security measures for both their professional and private activities.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.hurriyetdailynews.com/germany-warns-mps-with-turkish-roots-against-travel-to-turkey-reports.aspx?pageID=238&nID=100374&NewsCatID=351|title=Germany warns MPs with Turkish roots against travel to Turkey: Reports|work=H\u00fcrriyet Daily News|date=12 June 2016|accessdate=2019-03-19}}</ref>\n\nOn June 24, 2016, [[Pope Francis]] in a speech described the killing of Armenians as a genocide. Also, the Vatican spokesman [[Federico Lombardi]], told the reporters that \"There is no reason not to use this word in this case,\"  \"The reality is clear and we never denied what the reality is.\" Turkey condemned the declaration as \"very unfortunate\" and also said that it bore traces of \"the mentality of the Crusades.\"<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.hurriyetdailynews.com/pope-says-never-again-to-tragedies-like-armenian-genocide.aspx?pageID=238&nID=100893&NewsCatID=353|title=Pope says 'never again' to tragedies like 'Armenian genocide'|work=H\u00fcrriyet Daily News|date=25 June 2016|accessdate=2019-03-19}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.hurriyetdailynews.com/turkey-says-popes-armenian-genocide-declaration-bears-stamp-of-crusades-mentality-.aspx?pageID=238&nID=100900&NewsCatID=510|title=Turkey says pope's 'Armenian genocide' declaration bears stamp of 'Crusades' mentality' |work=H\u00fcrriyet Daily News|date=26 June 2016|accessdate=2019-03-19}}</ref>\n\nOn July 1, 2016, [[France]]'s lower house of parliament has unanimously voted to criminalize the denial of all crimes against humanity. The amendment covered all events which the French law defined as genocide, crimes against humanity, war crimes or slavery, including the Armenian Genocide. The law set out penalties of up to one year in prison and a 45,000-euro ($50,000) fine for those who contradicted it. It is yet to be passed by France's Senate.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.dw.com/en/french-parliament-votes-to-criminalize-denial-of-armenian-genocide/a-19372985|title=French parliament votes to criminalize denial of Armenian genocide|publisher=Deutsche Welle|date=2 July 2016|accessdate=2019-03-19}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|last=Pells|first= Rachael|url=https://www.independent.co.uk/news/world/armenian-genocide-french-mps-vote-denial-crime-criminalise-a7117091.html|title=French MPs vote to criminalise denial of Armenian genocide|work=The Independent|date=3 July 2016|accessdate=2019-03-19}}</ref><ref name=\"auto1\">{{cite news|url=http://www.hurriyetdailynews.com/turkish-foreign-ministry-calls-french-genocide-denial-bill-a-risk-to-freedom-of-expression.aspx?pageID=238&nID=101356&NewsCatID=510|title=Turkish Foreign Ministry calls French genocide denial bill a risk to freedom of expression|work=H\u00fcrriyet Daily News|date=7 July 2016|accessdate=2019-03-19}}</ref> Turkish Foreign Ministry said that this law is a risk to freedom of expression<ref name=\"auto1\"/>\n\nOn August 1, 2016, the [[Knesset]]'s Education, Culture and Sports Committee announced its recognition of the Armenian Genocide and urged the Israeli government to formally acknowledge the 1915 mass slaughter of 1.5 million Armenians as such.<ref>{{cite news|last=Newman|first=Marissa |url=http://www.timesofisrael.com/knesset-education-committee-recognizes-armenian-genocide|title=Knesset Education Committee recognizes Armenian genocide|work=The Times of Israel|date=1 August 2016|accessdate=2019-03-19}}</ref>\n\nOn September 17, 2016, the [[Andean Parliament]], a legislative body composed of representatives of [[Bolivia]], [[Colombia]], [[Ecuador]], [[Peru]] and [[Chile]], approved a resolution recognizing the \"Armenian Genocide perpetrated by the authorities of the Ottoman Empire between the years 1915\u20131923\" and condemning \"any policy of denial with respect to genocide and crimes against humanity suffered by the Armenian nation.\"<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.prensaarmenia.com.ar/2016/09/the-andean-parliament-recognized.html|title=The Andean Parliament Recognized the Armenian Genocide and Condemned Denialism|agency=Prensa Armenia|date=19 September 2016|accessdate=2019-03-19}}</ref>\n\nOn October 14, 2016, the [[French Senate]] \u2014the upper house of the Parliament of [[France]]\u2014approved a draft law criminalizing the denial of the Armenian Genocide. The bill, which was unanimously passed by the lower house of the French parliament on July 1, set out penalties of up to a year in prison and a 45,000 Euro (US$50,000) fine for those who publicly deny the genocide.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://armenianweekly.com/2016/10/14/french-senate-ag-denial|title=French Senate Approves Bill Criminalizing Armenian Genocide Denial|work=Armenian Weekly|date=14 October 2016|accessdate=2019-03-19}}</ref>\n\nOn January 26, 2017, the Parliament of [[Denmark]] approved a resolution that condemns Turkish legislation for banning citizens and mass media to use the term 'genocide' and that it is an unreasonable restriction on academic freedom and freedom of speech. The resolution also condemned the acts of violence committed against the Armenian people.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://armenpress.am/eng/news/876170/turkey%E2%80%99s-denial-of-armenian-genocide-is-%E2%80%9Cunreasonable-restriction%E2%80%9D-%E2%80%93-parliament-of-denmark.html|title=Turkey's denial of Armenian Genocide is \"unreasonable restriction\" \u2013 Parliament of Denmark|agency=Armenpress|date=26 January 2017|accessdate=2019-03-19}}</ref>\n\nIn a letter dated April 21, 2017 and addressed to the Armenian National Committee of America Western Region (ANCA-WR), Wyoming Governor [[Matt Mead]] has recognized the Armenian Genocide and praised the work of Armenian American grassroots. [[Wyoming]] became the 45th U.S. state to recognize the Armenian Genocide.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://armenianweekly.com/2017/04/21/wyoming-becomes-45th-u-s-state-to-recognize-the-armenian-genocide/|title=Wyoming Becomes 45th U.S. State to Recognize the Armenian Genocide|work=Armenian Weekly|date=21 April 2017|accessdate=2019-03-17}}</ref>\n\nOn April 25, 2017, the Parliament of the [[Czech Republic]] approved a resolution, condemning the genocide of Armenians and other religious and national minorities in the Ottoman Empire during the First World War.<ref>{{cite news |last=Ghazanchyan|first=Siranush|url= http://www.armradio.am/en/2017/04/26/czech-parliament-recognizes-the-armenian-genocide|title=Czech Republic Parliament recognizes the Armenian Genocide|publisher=Public Radio of Armenia|date=26 April 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170519202528/http://www.armradio.am/en/2017/04/26/czech-parliament-recognizes-the-armenian-genocide/|archive-date=2017-05-19}}</ref>\n\nOn May 19, 2017, the [[Texas House of Representatives]] unanimously passed House Resolution 191, titled \u201cRecognizing the Armenian Genocide\". [[Texas]] became the 46th U.S. State to recognize the Armenian Genocide.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://armenianweekly.com/2017/05/19/texas-recognizes-the-armenian-genocide-becomes-46th-state-to-acknowledge-the-crime|title=Texas Recognizes the Armenian Genocide; Becomes 46th State to Acknowledge the Crime|work=Armenian Weekly|date=19 May 2017|accessdate=2019-03-19}}</ref>\n\nOn August 24, 2017, [[Iowa]] Governor [[Kim Reynolds]] signed a proclamation memorializing the Armenian Genocide and declaring Oct. 2017 as \u201cArmenia Awareness Month\u201d in the Hawkeye State. Iowa is now the 47th U.S. state to officially recognize the Armenian Genocide.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://armenianweekly.com/2017/08/24/iowa-becomes-47th-state-to-officially-recognize-the-armenian-genocide|title=Iowa Becomes 47th State to Officially Recognize the Armenian Genocide|work=Armenian Weekly|date=24 August 2017|accessdate=2019-03-19}}</ref>\n\nOn November 6, 2017, [[Indiana]] Governor [[Eric Holcomb]] issued a powerful proclamation memorializing the Ottoman Turkish Empire's centrally planned and executed annihilation of close to three million Armenians, Greeks, Assyrians, and Syriacs, making the Hoosier State the 48th U.S. state to properly recognize and condemn the Armenian Genocide.<ref name=\"ReferenceA\"/>\n\nOn February 22, 2018, the parliament of the [[Netherlands]] adopted two resolutions on the Armenian Genocide with the absolute majority of the votes. The first resolution reaffirms the decision of the Netherlands in 2004 to recognize the Armenian Genocide, while by the second resolution the foreign minister of the Netherlands will be obliged to visit [[Armenia]] and pay tribute to the victims of the Armenian Genocide at Tsitsernakaberd memorial complex every 5 years.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://horizonweekly.ca/en/parliament-of-netherlands-reaffirms-the-2004-resolution-to-recognize-the-armenian-genocide|title=Parliament of Netherlands reaffirms the 2004 resolution to recognize the Armenian Genocide|publisher=Horizonweekly.ca}}</ref>\n\nOn November 21, 2018 [[Derby City Council]] in England, United Kingdom, passed a resolution in Full Council to recognise the Armenian Genocide.<ref name=\":2\">{{Cite web|url=https://artsakh.org.uk/2018/11/22/derby-city-council-england-uk-unanimously-passes-a-resolution-to-formally-recognise-the-armenian-genocide/|title=Derby City Council (England, UK) unanimously passes a resolution to formally recognise the Armenian Genocide|last=Pollard|first=Russell |date=22 November 2018|website=Artsakh.Org.UK|access-date=2019-01-09}}</ref>\n\nDue to ongoing deterioration of relations between Egypt and Turkey, the Government of Egypt led by el-Sisi, has been receiving proposal to recognize the Armenian Genocide, a sensitive subject which Turkey has many times denounced.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://anca.org/egypt-first-islamic-country-to-raise-armenian-genocide-issue-says-anc-egypt-chair/|title=Egypt First Islamic Country to Raise Armenian Genocide Issue says ANC Egypt Chair|date=November 29, 2016|publisher=}}</ref> Filmmaker Mohamed Hanafi had produced a movie, \"Who Killed the Armenians?\", in response to ongoing tensions between Turkey and Egypt, as an act of Egyptian solidarity to Armenia.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://anca.org/who-killed-the-armenians-egyptian-filmmakers-tackle-the-genocide/|title='Who Killed the Armenians?': Egyptian Filmmakers Tackle the Genocide|date=December 4, 2015|publisher=}}</ref> In February 2019, Abdel Fattah el-Sisi announced it had implicitly recognized the Armenian Genocide, further deteriorated the [[Egypt\u2013Turkey relations|relationship between Turkey and Egypt]].<ref name=\"egypttoday.com\"/>\n\nOn February 5, 2019, French President Emmanuel Macron declared April 24 as Armenian Genocide commemoration day in [[France]].<ref name=\"News.am\"/>\n\nOn March 20, 2019, [[Alabama]] became the 49th US state to formally recognize the Armenian Genocide.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://armenianweekly.com/2019/03/20/alabama-becomes-49th-u-s-state-to-recognize-the-armenian-genocide|title=Alabama Becomes 49th U.S. State to Recognize the Armenian Genocide|publisher=Armeniaweekly.com}}</ref>\n\nOn April 10, 2019, the Executive Committee of the [[Centrist Democrat International]] political alliance met in Brussels where participants officially adopted the resolution recognizing and condemning the Armenian Genocide.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://armenpress.am/eng/news/970821.html|title=Centrist Democrat International adopts resolution condemning Armenian Genocide|publisher=Armenpress.am}}</ref>\n\nOn April 10, 2019, the [[Italian Chamber of Deputies]] adopted an initiative calling on the Italian government to recognize the Armenian Genocide and give the issue an international dimension.<ref name=\"https\"/>\n\nOn April 26, 2019, the [[Parliament of Portugal]] adopted a resolution recognizing the Armenian Genocide.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://news.am/eng/news/509563.html|title=Parliament of Portugal recognizes Armenian Genocide|publisher=News.am}}</ref>\n\nOn October 29, 2019, the [[US House of Representatives]] passed a resolution on a 405\u201311 vote to recognize the Armenian genocide.<ref name=\":3\">{{cite web|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2019/10/29/us/politics/armenian-genocide-resolution.html|title=House Passes Resolution Recognizing Armenian Genocide|website=The New York Times|date=29 October 2019}}</ref> Moreover, the House backed a legislation calling on President [[Donald Trump]] to impose sanctions on Turkey,<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.euronews.com/2019/10/29/us-house-recognises-armenian-genocide-backs-turkey-sanctions|title=US House recognises Armenian genocide, backs Turkey sanctions|website=euronews|date=29 October 2019}}</ref> following the [[2019 Turkish offensive into north-eastern Syria|Turkish offensive into north-eastern Syria]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/powerpost/trumps-dealings-with-turkey-pave-way-for-house-vote-acknowledging-armenian-genocide/2019/10/29/00adb200-fa7d-11e9-8906-ab6b60de9124_story.html|title=Trump's dealings with Turkey pave way for House vote acknowledging Armenian genocide|website=The Washington Post|date=30 October 2019}}</ref> On December 12, 2019, the [[US Senate]] passed unanimously a resolution to recognize the genocide.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://edition.cnn.com/2019/12/12/politics/senate-armenian-genocide-resolution-passes/index.html|title=Senate passes resolution to formally 'commemorate the Armenian Genocide'|website=CNN|date=12 December 2019}}</ref>\n\nOn February 13, 2020, the [[Syrian Parliament]] unanimously adopted a resolution recognizing the Armenian Genocide.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.panarmenian.net/eng/news/277901/Syrian_Parliament_unanimously_recognizes_Armenian_Genocide|title=Syrian Parliament unanimously recognizes Armenian Genocide|publisher=Panarmenian.net}}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n{{Portal|Genocide|War}}\n\n* [[100th anniversary of the Armenian Genocide]]\n* [[Armenian Genocide denial]]\n* [[Armenian Genocide in culture]]\n* [[Armenian Genocide Remembrance Day]]\n* [[Armenian Secret Army for the Liberation of Armenia]]\n* [[List of visitors to Tsitsernakaberd]]\n* [[Press coverage during the Armenian Genocide]]\n* [[United States resolution on Armenian Genocide]]\n* [[Witnesses and testimonies of the Armenian Genocide]]\n\n==Notes==\n{{Reflist|group=note}}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n==External links==\n{{commons category-inline}}\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20131215113006/http://armenocide.am/International_recognition.html Armenian Genocide International Recognition]\n* [http://www.arak29.am/PDF_PPT/7-History/AfterGenocideRecognition.htm Arak29 Genocide Recognition (2000\u20132004)]\n* [http://www.english.rfi.fr/europe/20120125-frances-armenian-genocide-bill-who-what-where-why Radio France Internationale in English on French Armenian genocide laws]\n* [http://genocide.am/article/recognition_of_the_armenian_genocide.html Recognition of the Armenian Genocide: List of countries]\n\n{{Armenian Genocide}}\n{{Foreign relations of Armenia}}\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Recognition of the Armenian Genocide}}\n[[Category:Armenian Genocide]]\n[[Category:Armenian Genocide denial]]\n[[Category:Foreign relations of Armenia]]\n", "name_user": "Kiwipete", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200ePosition of France:Grammar revision", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Armenian_Genocide_recognition"}
